# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ireland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The **1841 Census of Ireland** was a census that covered the whole island of Ireland.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] It was conducted as part of the broader 1841 United Kingdom census, which was the first modern census undertaken in the UK.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The census is of particular note in Ireland as it was taken shortly before the Great Famine (1845–1852), which resulted in over 1 million deaths and spurred decades of mass emigration.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The total population of the island in 1841 was estimated to be just under 8.2 million, which remains the highest recorded population Ireland has ever had.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] During this year, Ireland also held about 31% of the UK's population.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] As of the latest censuses – 2022 in the Republic of Ireland and 2021 in Northern Ireland – the island's population stood at just over 7 million, roughly 16% lower than its pre-famine peak.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The original records of the 1821 to 1851 censuses were destroyed by fire at the Four Courts in Dublin during the Irish Civil War, while those between 1861 and 1891 were possibly pulped during the First World War.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Due to the Population Act 1840, the United Kingdom Census of 1841 was conducted using a different framework from that of earlier United Kingdom censuses.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The origins of the Population Act 1840 was the report of the 1830 Select Committee on the Population Bill, reprinted in 1840.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The subject of much speculation during the select committee hearings and report was the accuracy of previous census returns, the first national census being held in 1801.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Very few census records for Ireland prior to 1901 survive due to the Irish Public Office being bombed on 30 June 1922.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Some of the 1841 Census returns for Killeshandra of County Cavan, Kilcrohane of County Cork, Thurles of County Tipperary and Aghalurcher of County Fermanagh survived.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] In 1841 Cork was by far the island's most populous county, with approximately 850,000 residents - almost twice as populous as Galway in second place.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Although its population steadily declined for decades following the famine, Cork would remain Ireland's most populous county until the 1901 census, when it was surpassed by Antrim.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The least populous county was Carlow, which was also the sole county on the island with less than 100,000 residents.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Carlow was consistently recorded as Ireland's least populous county until the 1956 census, when Longford dropped below it.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Dublin was the most urbanised county in Ireland and had a population density of 405 people per square km.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] It was the only county to record an overall increase in population between 1841 and 1851, while the cities of Cork and Belfast also saw their populations rise in the immediate aftermath of the famine.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Partially owing to their mountainous terrain, counties Kerry, Donegal and Wicklow were the island's least densely populated regions.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Just 8 of Ireland's 32 counties currently have a population above their recorded 1841 peak as of the latest censuses.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] Population estimates suggest that the total population of the island peaked in 1845 at around 8.5 million, and would likely have reached 9 million at the 1851 census were it not for the famine.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] The census recorded that the population of England, Scotland and Wales combined was just over twice that of Ireland, at 18.55 million.
[src:ireland/1841-census-of-ireland] By comparison, 2020 estimates place the population of Great Britain at over nine times that of Ireland (65 million vs 6.9 million).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish component of the 1918 United Kingdom general election took place on 14 December 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the final United Kingdom general election to be held throughout Ireland, as the next election would happen following Irish independence.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It is a key moment in modern Irish history, seeing the overwhelming defeat of the moderate nationalist Irish Parliamentary Party (IPP), which had dominated the Irish political landscape since the 1880s, and a landslide victory for the radical Sinn Féin party.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin had never previously stood in a general election, but had won six seats in by-elections in 1917–1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had vowed in its manifesto to establish an independent Irish Republic.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster, however, the Unionist Party was the most successful party.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the elections, Sinn Féin's elected members refused to attend the British Parliament in Westminster (London), and instead formed a parliament in Dublin, the First Dáil Éireann ("Assembly of Ireland"), which declared Irish independence as a republic.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish War of Independence was conducted under this revolutionary government which sought international recognition, and set about the process of state-building.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The other parties elected in the election were invited by Sinn Féin to join in creating the Dáil Éireann, but declined and took up their seats at Westminster.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 a system called plural voting was in place in both Britain and Ireland.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting was a practice whereby one person might be able to vote multiple times in an election.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Property and business owners could vote both in the constituency where their property lay and that in which they lived, if the two were different.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This system often resulted in one person being able to cast multiple votes.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the newly formed Irish Free State this system was ended by the Electoral Act 1923 and was abolished in the UK by the Representation of the People Act 1948.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Plural voting remained in effect in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The 1918 election was held in the aftermath of World War I, the Easter Rising and the Conscription Crisis.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was the first general election to be held after the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It was thus the first election in which women over the age of 30, and all men over the age of 21, could vote.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Previously, all women and most working-class men had been excluded from voting.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In 1918 the whole of Ireland was a part of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and was represented in the British Parliament by 105 Members of Parliament (MPs).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Whereas in Great Britain most elected politicians were members of either the Liberal Party or the Conservative Party, from the early 1880s most Irish MPs were Irish nationalists, who sat together in the British House of Commons as the Irish Parliamentary Party.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP strove for Home Rule, that is, limited self-government for Ireland within the United Kingdom, and had been supported by most Irish people, especially the Catholic majority.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule was opposed by most Protestants in Ireland, who formed a majority of the population in parts of the northern province of Ulster but a minority in the rest of Ireland, and favoured maintenance of the Union with Great Britain (and were therefore called Unionists).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionists were supported by the Conservative Party, whereas from 1885 the Liberal Party was committed to enacting some form of Home Rule.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists eventually formed their own representation, first the Irish Unionist Party then the Ulster Unionist Party.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Home Rule appeared to have been finally achieved with the passing of the Home Rule Act 1914.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the implementation of the Act was temporarily postponed with the outbreak of World War I due to determined Ulster Unionists' resistance to the Act.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As the war prolonged and with the failure to make any progress on the issue, the more radical Sinn Féin began to grow in strength.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin was founded by Arthur Griffith in 1905.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He believed that Irish nationalists should emulate the *Ausgleich* of Hungarian nationalists who, in the 19th century under Ferenc Deák, had chosen to boycott the imperial parliament in Vienna and unilaterally established their own legislature in Budapest.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Griffith had favoured a peaceful solution based on 'dual monarchy' with Britain, that is two separate states with a single head of state and a limited central government to control matters of common concern only.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, by 1918, under its new leader Éamon de Valera, Sinn Féin had come to favour achieving separation from Britain by means of an armed uprising if necessary and the establishment of an independent republic.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the aftermath of the 1916 Easter Rising the party's ranks were swelled by participants and supporters of the rebellion as they were freed from British prisons and internment camps, and at its 1917 Ard Fheis (annual conference) de Valera was elected leader and the new, more radical policy adopted.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Prior to 1916, Sinn Féin had been a fringe movement having a limited cooperative alliance with William O'Brien's All-for-Ireland League and enjoyed little electoral success.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, between the Easter Rising of that year and the 1918 general election, the party's popularity increased dramatically.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin demonstrated its new electoral capability in four by-election successes in 1917 in which Count Plunkett, Joseph McGuinness, de Valera and W.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave were each elected, although it lost three by-elections in early 1918 before winning two more with Patrick McCartan and Arthur Griffith.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In one case there were unproven allegations of electoral fraud.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party had benefitted from a number of factors in the 1918 elections, including demographic changes and political factors.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate in 1918, as with the entire electorate throughout the United Kingdom, had changed in two major ways since the preceding general election.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Firstly, there was a "generational" change because of the First World War, which meant that the British general election due in 1915 had not taken place.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As a result, no election took place between 1910 and 1918, the longest gap in modern British and Irish constitutional history until then (it was superseded in Britain in 1935–45).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Secondly, the franchise had been greatly extended by the Representation of the People Act 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] This granted voting rights to women (albeit only those over 30) for the first time, and gave all men over 21 and military servicemen over 19 a vote in parliamentary elections without property qualifications.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish electorate increased from around 700,000 to about two million.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Overall, a new generation of young voters, and the sudden influx of women over thirty, meant that vast numbers of new voters of unknown voter affiliation existed, changing dramatically the composition of the Irish electorate.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Six MPs stood under a different political affiliation from the December 1910 general election.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] One MP stood under a different political affiliation from their by-election victory.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Voting in most Irish constituencies occurred on Saturday, 14 December 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] While the rest of the United Kingdom fought the 'Khaki election' on other issues involving the British parties, in Ireland four major political parties had national appeal.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] These were the IPP, Sinn Féin, the Irish Unionist Party and the Irish Labour Party.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Unionist Party favoured continuance of the union with Britain (along with its subordinate, the Ulster Unionist Labour Association, who fought as Labour Unionists).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] A number of other small nationalist parties also took part.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ireland had 105 seats elected from 103 constituencies.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Ninety-nine seats were elected from single-seat geographical constituencies under the first-past-the-post voting system.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There were two two-seat constituencies: Dublin University (Trinity College) elected two MPs under the single transferable vote and Cork City elected two MPs under the bloc voting system.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In addition to ordinary geographical constituencies there were three university constituencies: the Queen's University of Belfast (which returned a Unionist), Dublin University (which returned two Unionists) and the National University (which returned a member of Sinn Féin).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 105 seats, 25 were uncontested, with a Sinn Féin candidate winning unopposed.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Seventeen of these seats were in Munster.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In some cases it was because there was a certain winner in Sinn Féin.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dillon was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1880.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He resigned in 1883 but was re-elected in 1885.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Donovan contested the Donegal South constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Esmonde was first elected to the Dublin South constituency in 1885.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell contested the Longford constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Farrell was first elected to the Cavan West constituency in 1895.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Hazleton contested the Louth constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Kilbride was first elected to the Kerry South constituency in 1887.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He retired in 1900 but was re-elected in 1903.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Meehan contested the Queen's County constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Nugent contested the Dublin St Michan's constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor was first elected to the Tipperary constituency in 1885.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1892 but regained it in 1905.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Dowd was first elected to the Sligo North constituency in 1900.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Shee contested the Waterford County constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch contested the Battersea South constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Lynch was first elected to the Galway Borough constituency in 1901.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] He lost his seat in 1903 following his conviction but was re-elected in 1909.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Stepney Limehouse constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Gwynn contested the Dublin University constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sheehan contested the Westmeath constituency in 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In this election, 75 candidates who had never previously been elected to Parliament were elected.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin candidates won 73 seats out of 105, but four party candidates (Arthur Griffith, Éamon de Valera, Eoin MacNeill and Liam Mellows) were elected for two constituencies and so the total number of individual Sinn Féin MPs elected was 69.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Despite the isolated allegations of intimidation and electoral fraud on the part of both republicans and unionists, the election was seen as a landslide victory for Sinn Féin.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin received 46.9% of votes island-wide, and 65% of votes in the area that became the Irish Free State.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, the 46.9% is not the total result of the overall success of Sinn Féin.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That figure only accounts for 48 seats that they won because in 25 of the other constituencies the other parties did not contest them, and Sinn Féin won them unopposed.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Most of these constituencies were Sinn Féin strongholds.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It has been estimated that, had the 25 seats been contested, Sinn Féin would have received at least 53% of the vote island-wide.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, this is a conservative estimate and the percentage would likely have been higher.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin also did not contest four seats due to a deal with the IPP (see below).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Labour, who had pulled out in the south under instructions to 'wait', polled better in Belfast than Sinn Féin.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Within the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, Sinn Féin achieved 400,269 votes in the contested seats out of 606,117 total votes cast which amounted to a huge landslide of 66.0% in the vote and winning 70 out of the 75 constituencies.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Unionist Party won 22 seats and 25.3% of the vote island-wide (29.2% when Labour Unionist candidates are included), becoming the second-largest party in terms of MPs.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The success of the unionists, who won 26 seats overall, was largely limited to Ulster.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Otherwise, southern unionists were elected only in the constituencies of Rathmines and Dublin University which returned two.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that later became the Irish Free State and then the Republic of Ireland, the Irish Unionist Alliance polled 37,218 votes from 101,839 total votes cast for other parties in the constituencies that they stood a candidate.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, if all of the total votes in the contested seats where the Irish Unionist Alliance did not stand are included there was a total of 606,117 votes cast, which converts the Irish Unionist Alliance share of the vote in the 26 counties to just 6.1%.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] With the one Independent Unionist being elected for Dublin University adding 0.1% in total with 793 votes to give 6.2% across the 26 counties and only 3 seats won by the Unionists.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP suffered a catastrophic defeat including the loss of its leader, John Dillon.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] It won only six seats in Ireland, its losses exaggerated by the "first-past-the-post" system which gave it a share of seats far short of its much larger share of the vote (21.7%) and the number of seats it would have won under a "proportional representation" ballot system.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] All but one of its seats were in Ulster.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The exception was Waterford City, the seat previously held by John Redmond, who had died earlier in the year, and retained by his son Captain William Redmond.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Four of their Ulster seats were part of the deal to avoid unionist victories which saved some for the party but may have cost it the support of Protestant voters elsewhere.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP came close to winning other seats in County Louth and Wexford South, and in general their support held up better in the north and east of the island.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The party was represented in Westminster by seven MPs because T.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] O'Connor won the Liverpool Scotland seat he had held since the 1885 election due to Irish emigrant votes.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The remnants of the IPP in time became the Nationalist Party of Northern Ireland under the leadership of Joseph Devlin.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the 26 counties that became the Irish Free State, the Irish Parliamentary Party won 181,320 votes out of 606,117 total votes cast in the contested seats, amounting to a 26.0% vote share.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] If the Independent Home Rule Nationalists are included there were 11,162 votes which comes to 1.8% and a vote share of 27.8% for the Nationalists.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Irish Parliamentary Party held on to just 2 seats in the 26 counties that became Southern Ireland and then the Irish Free State.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In Ulster (nine counties), Unionists won 23 out of the 38 seats with Sinn Féin gaining ten and the Irish Parliamentary Party five.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was a limited electoral pact brokered by Roman Catholic Cardinal Michael Logue in December between Sinn Féin and the Nationalist IPP in eight seats.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] However, it only concluded after nominations closed.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin instructed its supporters to vote IPP in Armagh South, despite no Unionist candidate (79 SF votes), Down South (33 SF votes for Éamon de Valera), Tyrone North-East (56 SF votes) and Donegal East (46 SF votes).
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The IPP instructed its supporters to vote Sinn Féin in Fermanagh South (132 IPP votes) which had no Unionist candidate, Londonderry City (120 IPP votes) where Eoin MacNeill narrowly beat the Unionist, and Tyrone North-West also against a Unionist but where no IPP candidate was nominated.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The discipline of voters, when faced with two rival nationalist candidates and with only a post-nomination pact, was impressive.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The pact only broke down in Down East where a Unionist won as the IPP candidate refused to participate, thus splitting the Catholic nationalist vote.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] There was no pact in Belfast Falls which Joe Devlin (IPP) won with 8,488 votes against 3,245 for Éamon de Valera (SF) although no Unionist stood.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The only other Belfast seat contested by both nationalist parties was Duncairn against Edward Carson; otherwise, Sinn Féin stood alone in seven seats reaching double figures in two.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Monaghan North was won by Sinn Féin's Ernest Blythe in a three-cornered fight against both IPP and Unionist candidates.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the Monaghan South, and Donegal North, South and West seats, despite no Unionist standing, Sinn Féin won all four against IPP candidates.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Sinn Féin took the two (uncontested) Cavan seats with Arthur Griffith taking his second in Cavan East as well as that of Tyrone North West.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In six contested seats no Unionist stood.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Unionists won a clear majority of the 38 Ulster seats including eight of the nine in Belfast.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In the six Ulster counties which formed the future Northern Ireland, Unionists won 23 of the 30 seats.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On 21 January 1919, 27 (out of 101 elected) members representing thirty constituencies answered the roll of Dáil Éireann—the Irish for "Assembly of Ireland".
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Invitations to attend the Dáil had been sent to all 100 men and one woman who had been elected on 14 December 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Eoin MacNeill had been elected for both Londonderry City and the National University of Ireland.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Thirty-three republicans were unable to attend as they were in prison, most of them without trial since 17 May 1918.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Pierce McCan (of Tipperary East), who died in prison, would have brought the total to thirty-four.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Of the 69 republicans elected, most had fought in the Easter Rising.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] In accordance with the Sinn Féin manifesto, their elected members refused to attend Westminster, having instead formed their own parliament.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Dáil Éireann was, according to John Patrick McCarthy, the revolutionary government under which the Irish War of Independence was fought and which sought international recognition.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Maryann Gialanella Valiulis says that having justified its existence, the Dáil provided itself with a theoretical framework and set about the process of state-building.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] After having dominated Irish politics for four decades, the IPP was so decimated by its massive defeat that it dissolved soon after the election.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] As mentioned above, its remains became the Northern Ireland-based Nationalist Party, which survived in Northern Ireland until 1969.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The British administration and unionists refused to recognise the Dáil.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] At its first meeting attended by 27 deputies (others were still imprisoned or impaired) on 21 January 1919 the Dáil issued a Declaration of Independence and proclaimed itself the parliament of a new state, the Irish Republic.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] On the same day, in unconnected circumstances, two members of the Royal Irish Constabulary guarding gelignite were killed in the Soloheadbeg Ambush by members of the Irish Volunteers.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Although it had not ordered this incident, the course of events soon drove the Dáil to recognise the Volunteers as the army of the Irish Republic and the ambush as an act of war against Great Britain.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Volunteers therefore changed their name, in August, to the Irish Republican Army.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The train of events set in motion by the elections would eventually bring about the creation of the Irish Free State as a British dominion in 1922.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] That state became the first internationally recognised independent Irish state in 1931, when the Statute of Westminster removed virtually all of the UK Parliament's remaining authority over the Free State and the other dominions.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The Free State eventually evolved into the modern Republic of Ireland.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The leaders of the Sinn Féin candidates elected in 1918, such as de Valera, Michael Collins and W.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] Cosgrave, came to dominate Irish politics.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] De Valera, for example, would hold some form of elected office from his first election as an MP in a by-election in 1917 until 1973.
[src:ireland/1918-united-kingdom-general-election-in-ireland] The two major parties in the Republic of Ireland today, Fianna Fáil and Fine Gael, are both descendants of Sinn Féin, which first enjoyed substantial electoral success in 1918.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The **1958 FIFA World Cup** was the sixth FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for senior national teams.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It was played in Sweden from 8 to 29 June 1958.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It is the only Nordic country to have hosted a FIFA World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Brazil beat Sweden 5–2 in the final in Solna, Stockholm, to claim their first title, having beaten France in the semifinal and Wales in the quarterfinal.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The tournament also marked the arrival of Pelé on the world stage, at age 17.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] He scored in all three of Brazil's knockout games.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] French striker Just Fontaine scored 13 goals, which is, as of 2026, still the record for most goals scored in a single tournament.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This was the first appearance of Wales at the FIFA World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] They did not qualify for another until 2022.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This tournament also marked the debuts of Northern Ireland, as well as the Soviet Union.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Defending champions West Germany were eliminated by runners-up Sweden and lost to France in the match for third place.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Argentina, Chile, Mexico, and Sweden expressed interest in hosting the tournament.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Swedish delegates lobbied other countries at the FIFA Congress held in Rio de Janeiro around the opening of the 1950 World Cup finals.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Sweden was awarded the 1958 tournament unopposed on 23 June 1950.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The hosts (Sweden) and the defending champions (West Germany) qualified automatically.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Of the remaining 14 places, nine were allocated to Europe, three to South America, one to North/Central America, and one to Asia/Africa.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Aside from the main European zone matches, Wales, which finished second in its group behind Czechoslovakia, was drawn into a play-off with Israel after Israel won its group by default because its three opponents, Turkey, Indonesia and Sudan, refused to play.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] FIFA had imposed a rule that no team would qualify without playing at least one match, something that had happened in several previous World Cups.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Wales won the play-off and qualified for the first time (something they did not do again until 2022).
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] With Northern Ireland making its debut, and England and Scotland also qualifying, this World Cup was the only one to date to feature all four of the United Kingdom’s Home Nations.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This World Cup also featured the entry and qualification of the Soviet Union for the first time, while Argentina appeared for the first time since 1934.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It was also the first one for which Italy failed to qualify (Italy did not take part in the 1930 tournament but there was no qualification for that competition).
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Other teams that failed to qualify included two-time champions and 1954 semifinalists Uruguay, as well as Spain and Belgium.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] On 8 February 1958, in Solna, Lennart Hyland and Sven Jerring presented the results of the draw in which the qualified teams were divided into four groups.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Seeding was geographical rather than by team strength, with each group containing one western European team, one eastern European team, one of the four British teams that had qualified, and one from the Americas.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The following 16 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The format of the competition changed from 1954: 16 teams still competed in four groups of four, but this time each team played each of the other teams in its group at least once, without extra time in the event of a draw.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Two points were awarded for a win and one point for a draw.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] If the first two teams finished on equal points, then goal average (or goal ratio) decided their placements.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] As in 1954, if the second- and third-placed teams finished on the same points, then there would be a play-off with the winner going through.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] If a play-off resulted in a draw, goal average from the group games would be used to determine who went through to the next round.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] If the goal averages were equal, then lots would have been drawn.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] By the time the competition began, these arrangements were still in discussion.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Some teams complained that a play-off match, meaning three games in five days, was too much, and before the second round of group matches, FIFA informed the teams that goal average would be used before resorting to a play-off.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This was overturned when the Swedish Football Association complained, stating that it was wrong to change the rules mid-tournament, but also because it wanted the extra revenue from playoff matches.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This was the first time that goal average was available to separate teams in a World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It was used to separate the teams finishing first and second in one of the groups.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] However, all three playoffs finished with decisive results and so it was not needed to separate the teams involved in a tied playoff.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Almost all the matches kicked off simultaneously in each of the three rounds of the group phase, as did the quarterfinals and semifinals.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The exceptions were Sweden's three group matches, all of which were televised by Sveriges Radio; these started at other times so Swedes could attend other matches without missing their own team's.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Apart from these, one match per round was televised, and relayed across Europe by the European Broadcasting Union (EBU).
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Many Swedes bought their first television for the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The official ball was the "Top-Star VM-bollen 1958" model made by Sydsvenska Läder & Remfabriks AB (aka "Remmen" or "Sydläder") in Ängelholm.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Four FIFA officials conducted a blind test to choose it from 102 candidates.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In Group 4, Pelé and Garrincha did not play until the last of Brazil's group games, against the Soviet Union.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Pelé failed to score, but provided the assist to Vavá's second goal.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Brazil won the game 2–0 (also thanks to an impressive exhibition of dribbling prowess by Garrincha) and the group by two points.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Previously, they had drawn 0–0 with England in what was the first ever goalless game in World Cup history.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Eventually, the Soviet Union and England went to a playoff game, in which Anatoli Ilyin scored in the 67th minute to knock England out, while Austria had already been eliminated.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The English side had been weakened by the Munich air disaster earlier in the year, which killed three internationals on the books of Manchester United, including England's young star Duncan Edwards.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Playoffs were also needed in Group 1 (Northern Ireland beat Czechoslovakia to join the defending champions West Germany in the quarterfinals) and Group 3 (Wales topped Hungary to advance with hosts Sweden).
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Hungary had become a spent force after their appearance in the final of the previous tournament.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] They had lost their best players two years before, when they fled in the wake of the failed uprising against the communist regime.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In a rather restrictive sense, from the 1954 team, only goalkeeper Gyula Grosics, defender Jozsef Bozsik and forward Nándor Hidegkuti remained.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In Group 2, Scotland faced Yugoslavia, Paraguay, and France.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] France topped the group, with Just Fontaine netting six goals.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Yugoslavia finished second, while Scotland came in last.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the quarterfinals, France's Just Fontaine continued his group stage form, managing another two goals as France triumphed over Northern Ireland.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] West Germany's Helmut Rahn put them into the semifinals with a single goal against Yugoslavia, while Sweden went through at the expense of the Soviet Union.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the other quarterfinal, Pelé scored the only goal for Brazil against Wales.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the other semifinal, Brazil and France were tied 1–1 for much of the first half.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] However, 36 minutes into the game, French captain and most experienced defender Robert Jonquet suffered a broken leg in a clash with Vavá, and France was down to ten men for the rest of the game.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Brazil dominated the rest of the match, as a Pelé hat-trick gave them a 5–2 victory.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Fontaine of France added one goal to his impressive tally.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the match for third place, Fontaine scored four more goals as France defeated West Germany 6–3.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This brought his total to 13 goals in one competition, a record that still stands.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The final was played in Solna, in the Råsunda Stadium; 50,000 people watched as the Brazilians went a goal down after four minutes.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] However, Vavá equalised shortly afterwards and then put them a goal ahead before half time.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the second half, Pelé outshone everyone, notching two goals.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] For the first one, he lobbed the ball over Bengt Gustavsson then followed it with a precise volley shot.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Zagallo added a goal in between, and Sweden managed a consolation goal.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the final, many World Cup records were set that still stand as of 2018.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] At age 17, Pelé simultaneously became the youngest player to participate in, score, and win a World Cup final.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Conversely, Nils Liedholm became the oldest player to score in a World Cup Final at 35 years 263 days.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This final had the highest number of goals scored by a winning team (5), the highest number of total goals scored (7), and together with the 1970 and 1998 finals shares the highest goal margin of difference (3); Brazil played in all those three finals.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The game is also notable for many firsts in FIFA World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] With the exception of the 1950 FIFA World Cup final group stage, this marked the first time that a World Cup host reached the final without winning it.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Additionally, the match marked the first time two nations from different continents (Europe and South America) met in a World Cup final.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It also marks the first and only World Cup hosted in Europe not won by a European team, a feat mirrored in 2014, when a World Cup hosted in the Americas was not won by a team from the Americas for the first time, when Germany beat Argentina 1–0 in the final.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It is also presently the only FIFA World Cup when all teams earned at least one point in the group stage.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] A total of twelve cities throughout the central and southern parts of Sweden hosted the tournament.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] FIFA regulations required at least six stadiums to have a capacity of at least 20,000.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] If Denmark had qualified, the organisers had planned to use the Idrætsparken in Copenhagen for Denmark's group matches.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Idrætsparken was renovated in 1956 with this in mind, but Denmark lost out to England in qualification.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] When doubts arose about whether funding would be forthcoming for rebuilding the Ullevi and Malmö Stadion, the organisers considered stadiums in Copenhagen and Oslo as contingency measures.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Råsunda Stadium was expanded from 38,000 for the World Cup by building end stands.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Organising committee chairman Holger Bergérus mortgaged his house to pay for this.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The new Malmö Stadion was built for the World Cup, replacing the 1896 Malmö Stadion at a new site.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Idrottsparken had 4,709 seats added for the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Social Democratic municipal government refused to pay for this until the organisers threatened to select Folkungavallen in Linköping instead.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] At the Rimnersvallen, a stand from the smaller Oddevallen stadium was moved to Rimnersvallen for the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Austria was estimated at 21,000, with more looking in from the adjoining hillside.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The most used stadium was the Råsunda Stadium in Stockholm, which hosted 8 matches, including the final, followed by the Ullevi Stadium in Gothenburg (the biggest stadium used during the tournament), which hosted 7 matches.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Malmö Stadium hosted 4 matches, Norrköping hosted 3 matches; Borås, Halmstad, Helsingborg, Västerås, and Sandviken hosted 2 matches each, and Örebro, Eskilstuna, and Uddevalla each hosted 1 match.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] 22 match officials were assigned to the tournament to serve as referees and assistant referees.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] There was no seeding for this World Cup; the teams were instead allocated geographically into four pots chosen by the FIFA World Cup Organisers.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Teams were drawn from each pot into Groups 1–4 in numerical order.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Preventing the defending champions from meeting the hosts in the group stage, either by seeding or predetermined group positions, was a practiced tradition throughout the history of the FIFA World Cup, with 1934 and 1954 being the only two exceptions.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] This tradition continued in 1958, with West Germany as defending champion and host nation Sweden both being allocated into the same *Western European Pot*, which kept them from meeting in the group stage.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The geographical basis of the seeding attracted criticism, especially from Austria, who were drawn against the teams considered strongest in each of the other three pots.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1958 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The West Germans, surprise world champions four years before, were still very strong, and fielded a young forward with lots of potential in Uwe Seeler.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Germans had to contend with a tournament favorites in Argentina's team, competing for the first time since 1934.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Argentina had been given a chance of reaching the semifinals or even winning the World Cup this time.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Czechoslovakia was a fairly strong team with a rich football tradition, and was considered to be no walkover for the West Germans or the Argentinians.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Northern Ireland had qualified for the tournament after defeating two-time world champions Italy during World Cup qualifying despite being considered underdogs.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] They ultimately advanced to the quarterfinals of the World Cup Finals by defeating Czechoslovakia in a play-off match, cited as one of the major upsets in early World Cup history.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Argentina experienced a horrible blow finishing last in the group with a −5 goal differential.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Arriving home, the Argentinian team met the wrath of several thousand angry football fans at Ezeiza Airport in Buenos Aires.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The second group had the largest number of goals scored in a single group in the 1958 World Cup, with 31 goals in total (~5.16 goals per game).
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Just Fontaine of France scored 6 of his 13 goals in the tournament, making him the tournament's top scorer going into the quarterfinals.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The teams in this group had not achieved significant success in past World Cups.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] France, even as hosts in 1938, did not secure notable achievements; Yugoslavia failed to match their 1930 semifinal run; and both Paraguay and Scotland entered the tournament as underdogs.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] France won the group ahead of Yugoslavia and went on to finish third.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Swedish hosts could count themselves lucky in ending up in a rather weak group, which they proceeded to win fairly easily with their powerful, workmanlike football.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The group included Hungary which had been considered by far the best team in the world some years ago, although the Hungarians could not beat West Germany in the final of the World Cup in 1954.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] But the Hungarian team had been dealt a blow by the Hungarian Revolution of 1956 after which star players like Sándor Kocsis and Ferenc Puskás left their homeland.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Striker Nándor Hidegkuti was still playing, but he was 36 years old and nowhere near his peak form.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In spite of Hungary's recent travails, they were still considered a strong side and were expected to advance from their group.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The success of Wales was a surprise but they drew all their group games and beat the Hungarians in a play-off match to follow Sweden into the knockout stage.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Wales played Brazil in the quarterfinals and became the recipient of young Pelé's first World Cup goal.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The 1–1 draw between Wales and Mexico was the first point scored by Mexico in a World Cup, having lost all eight matches in their previous three appearances in the World Cup, as well as their first match in this group against Sweden.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] To date, no other team has ever lost nine consecutive games in the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The match between Hungary and Wales in Sandviken became the northernmost World Cup match in history.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Despite setbacks in earlier tournaments, Brazil was still regarded as a formidable force, a reputation that they justified.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Soviet Union, having clinched the Olympic gold in 1956, and Austria, securing the bronze medal at the 1954 World Cup in Switzerland, were also strong contenders.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] England, despite being weakened by the tragic Munich air disaster that claimed several players, remained a team of considerable strength.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In the end, this group had the highest average attendance (31,320 per game), even higher than Group 3 with the host nation, Sweden.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The quality of the football in this group did not quite live up to expectations, however.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Only 15 goals were scored in the whole group, only one more than Group 3.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] And when England and Brazil drew 0–0, it was the first time in World Cup history that a game ended goalless.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] It was also the first time Brazil had failed to score in a World Cup finals match.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Brazil won the group without conceding a single goal.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The teenage Pelé played Brazil's last game against the Soviet Union.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] He did not score but drew wild reviews for his play.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The Soviet Union, in their first World Cup, took second place.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] With 13 goals, Just Fontaine was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] As of 2026, no player has ever scored more goals in a single FIFA World Cup Final stage.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In total, 126 goals were scored by 60 players, with none of them credited as an own goal.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] Although Just Fontaine got more votes than any other forward, they were split between the left and right inside forward positions.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The All-Star Team scored 12 goals in total.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:ireland/1958-fifa-world-cup] The 1958 FIFA World Cup is depicted in the 2016 American film *Pelé: Birth of a Legend* which is centered around Pelé and the Brazilian team's journey to winning the tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The **1982 FIFA World Cup** was the 12th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams, and was played in Spain from 13 June to 11 July 1982.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament was won by Italy, who defeated West Germany 3–1 in the final held in the Santiago Bernabéu Stadium in Madrid.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was Italy's third World Cup title, but their first since 1938.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The defending champions, Argentina, were eliminated in the second round (finishing third and last in their group).
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Algeria, Cameroon, Honduras, Kuwait and New Zealand made their first appearances in the finals.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament featured the first penalty shootout in World Cup competition.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the third and last World Cup to feature two rounds of group stages.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was also the third time (after 1934 and 1966) that all four semi-finalists were European.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the first round of Group 3, Hungary defeated El Salvador 10–1, equalling the largest margin of victory recorded in the finals (Hungary over South Korea 9–0 in 1954, and Yugoslavia over Zaire 9–0 in 1974).
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Although successful and filled with compelling and entertaining matches, this tournament also was blighted by violent fouls, some poor officiating, some overcrowded stadiums, very hot weather in some cities and alleged collusion between teams.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] One particular incident of note was West German goalkeeper Harald Schumacher's foul of French player Patrick Battiston during a semi-final match in Seville, and another was Italian player Claudio Gentile's intense and often violent match-long fouling and marking of Argentine player Diego Maradona.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA changed the regulations to somewhat prevent this kind of brutality on the pitch for the subsequent tournament in Mexico.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain was chosen as the host nation by FIFA in London on 6 July 1966.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hosting rights for the 1974 and 1978 tournaments were awarded at the same time.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] West Germany and Spain were initially competing for a hosting bid, but ultimately agreed a deal whereby Spain would support West Germany for the 1974 tournament and West Germany would allow Spain to bid for the 1982 World Cup unopposed.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] As a result, West Germany withdrew its bid for the 1982 edition.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The decision to host the World Cup in Spain was controversial: At the time of Spain being selected, the country was still under the dictatorship of Francisco Franco's regime.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, the regime of Francoist Spain ended by 1975 with the death of Franco.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The World Cup had significant effects on Spanish society after the democratic transition because, from the period from 1975 to 1982, Spain was still undergoing a transition from dictatorship to democracy.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] For the first time ever, the World Cup finals expanded from 16 to 24 teams.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This allowed more countries to participate from Africa and Asia.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Northern Ireland qualified for the first time since 1958.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Belgium, Czechoslovakia, El Salvador, England and the Soviet Union were all back in the finals after 12-year absences.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] England had its first successful World Cup qualifying campaign in 20 years (they qualified for the 1966 tournament as hosts and for the 1970 tournament as defending champions).
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Yugoslavia and Chile were also back after missing the 1978 tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Algeria, Cameroon, Honduras, Kuwait, and New Zealand all participated in the World Cup for the first time.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the first time that all six confederations (AFC, CAF, CONCACAF, CONMEBOL, OFC and UEFA) sent representative teams to the tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The following 24 teams qualified for the final tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the last time El Salvador qualified for the World Cup finals, the only time Kuwait have qualified, and the last time Mexico (who were disqualified from 1990) and South Korea failed to qualify.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The first round was a round-robin group stage containing six groups of four teams each.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two points were awarded for a win and one for a draw, with goal difference used to separate teams equal on points.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The top two teams in each group advanced.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the second round, the twelve remaining teams were split into four groups of three teams each, with the winner of each group progressing to the knockout semi-final stage.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The composition of the groups in the second round was determined before the start of the tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Groups A and B were to include one team from each of Groups 1 through 6, and Groups C and D included the remaining six teams.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winners of Groups 1 and 3 were in Group A while the runners-up were in Group C.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winners of Groups 2 and 4 were in Group B while the runners-up were in Group D.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winner of Group 5 was in Group D and the runner-up was in Group B.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winner of Group 6 was in Group C and the runner-up was in Group A.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thus, Group A mirrored Group C, and Group B mirrored Group D with the winners and runners-up from the first round being placed into opposite groups in the second round.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The second-round groups that mirrored each other (based on the first-round groupings) faced off against each other in the semi-finals.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thus, the Group A winner played the Group C winner, and the Group B winner played the Group D winner.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This meant that if two teams which played in the same first-round group both emerged from the second round, they would meet for the second time of the tournament in a semifinal match.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] It also guaranteed that the final match would feature two teams that had not previously played each other in the tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] As it turned out, Italy and Poland who were both in Group 1 in the first round, each won their second-round groups and played each other in a semifinal match.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Group 1, newcomers Cameroon held both Poland and Italy to draws, and were denied a place in the next round on the basis of having scored fewer goals than Italy (the sides had an equal goal difference).
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Poland and Italy qualified over Cameroon and Peru.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italian journalists and tifosi criticised their team for their uninspired performances that managed three draws; the squad was reeling from the recent Serie A scandal, where national players were suspended for match fixing and illegal betting.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group 2 featured one of the great World Cup upsets on the first day, the 2–1 victory of Algeria over reigning European Champions West Germany.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final match in the group, West Germany met Austria in a match later dubbed as the "Disgrace of Gijón".
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Algeria had already played their final group game on the previous day, and West Germany and Austria knew that a West German win by one or two goals would qualify them both, while a larger German victory would qualify Algeria over Austria, and a draw or an Austrian win would eliminate the Germans.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] After 10 minutes of all-out attack, West Germany scored a goal by Horst Hrubesch.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] After that solitary goal, the two teams kicked the ball around aimlessly for the rest of the match.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Chants of "*Fuera, fuera*" ("*Out, out*") were screamed by the Spanish crowd, while angry Algerian supporters waved banknotes at the players.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This performance was widely deplored, even by the German and Austrian fans.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] One German fan was so upset by his team's display that he burned his German flag in disgust.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Algeria protested to FIFA, who ruled that the result would stand; FIFA introduced a revised qualification system at subsequent World Cups in which the final two games in each group were played simultaneously.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Group 3, which featured the opening ceremony and first match of the tournament, Belgium defeated the defending champion Argentina 1–0.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Camp Nou stadium was the home of Barcelona, and many fans had wanted to see the club's new signing, Argentinian star Diego Maradona, who did not perform to expectations.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group 4 opened with England midfielder Bryan Robson's goal against France after only 27 seconds of play.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] England won 3–1 and qualified along with France over Czechoslovakia and Kuwait, though the tiny Gulf emirate held Czechoslovakia to a 1–1 draw.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the game between Kuwait and France, with France leading 3–1, France midfielder Alain Giresse scored a goal vehemently contested by the Kuwait team, who had stopped play after hearing a piercing whistle from the stands, which they thought had come from Soviet referee Miroslav Stupar.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Play had not yet resumed when Sheikh Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, brother of the then-Kuwaiti Emir and president of the Kuwait Football Association, rushed onto the pitch to remonstrate with the referee.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Stupar reversed his initial decision and disallowed the goal to the fury of the French.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Maxime Bossis scored another valid goal a few minutes later and France won 4–1.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Group 5, Honduras held hosts Spain to a 1–1 draw.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Northern Ireland won the group outright, eliminating Yugoslavia and beating hosts Spain 1–0; Northern Ireland had to play the majority of the second half with ten men after Mal Donaghy was dismissed.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain narrowly avoided elimination due to a huge referee error, securing a contentious 2–1 victory over Yugoslavia, largely attributed to a disputed penalty decision.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] At 17 years and 41 days, Northern Ireland forward Norman Whiteside was the youngest player to appear in a World Cup match.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] With Zico, Sócrates, Falcão, Éder and others, they boasted an offensive firepower that promised a return to the glory days of 1970.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat the USSR 2–1 thanks to a 20-metre Éder goal two minutes from time, then Scotland and New Zealand with four goals each.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviets took the group's other qualifying berth on goal difference at the expense of the Scots.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Poland opened Group A with a 3–0 defeat of Belgium thanks to a Zbigniew Boniek hat-trick.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet Union prevailed 1–0 in the next match over Belgium.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Poles edged out the USSR for the semi-final spot on the final day on goal difference thanks to a 0–0 draw in a politically charged match, as Poland's then-Communist government had imposed a martial law a few months earlier to quash internal dissent.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Group B, a match between England and West Germany ended in a goalless draw.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] West Germany put the pressure on England in their second match by beating Spain 2–1.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The home side drew 0–0 against England, denying Ron Greenwood's team a semi-final place and putting England in the same position as Cameroon, being eliminated without losing a game.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Group C, with Brazil, Argentina and Italy, in the opener, Italy prevailed 2–1 over Diego Maradona and Mario Kempes's side after a game in which Italian defenders Gaetano Scirea and Claudio Gentile proved themselves equal to the task of stopping the Argentinian attack.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina now needed a win over Brazil on the second day, but lost 3–1 – Argentina only scoring in the last minute.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Maradona kicked Brazilian player João Batista in the groin and was sent off in the 85th minute.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The match between Brazil and Italy pitted Brazil's attack against Italy's defence, with the majority of the game played around the Italian area, and with the Italian midfielders and defenders returning the repeated set volleys of Brazilian shooters such as Zico, Sócrates and Falcão.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italian centre back Gentile was assigned to mark Brazilian striker Zico, earning a yellow card and a suspension for the semi-final.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Paolo Rossi opened the scoring when he headed in Antonio Cabrini's cross with just five minutes played.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Sócrates equalised for Brazil seven minutes later.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the twenty-fifth minute Rossi stepped past Júnior, intercepted a pass from Cerezo across the Brazilians' goal, and drilled the shot home.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Brazilians threw everything in search of another equaliser, while Italy defended bravely.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 68 minutes, Falcão collected a pass from Júnior and as Cerezo's dummy run distracted three defenders, fired home from 20 yards out.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Both aimed at the same shot, Rossi connecting to get a hat trick and sending Italy into the lead for good.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the 86th minute Giancarlo Antognoni scored an apparent fourth goal for Italy, but it was wrongly disallowed for offside.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the dying moments Dino Zoff made a miraculous save to deny Oscar a goal, ensuring that Italy advanced to the semi-final.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the last group, Group D, France dispatched Austria 1–0 with a free kick goal by Bernard Genghini, and then defeated Northern Ireland 4–1 to reach their first semi-final since 1958.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In a re-match of the encounter in the first round, Italy beat Poland in the first semi-final through two goals from Paolo Rossi.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the game between France and West Germany, the Germans opened the scoring through a Pierre Littbarski strike in the 17th minute, and the French equalised nine minutes later with a Michel Platini penalty.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the second half a long through ball sent French defender Patrick Battiston racing clear towards the German goal.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] With both Battiston and the lone German defender trying to be the first to reach the ball, Battiston flicked it past German keeper Harald Schumacher from the edge of the German penalty area and Schumacher reacted by jumping up to block.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Schumacher did not seem to go for the ball, however, and clattered straight into the oncoming Battiston – which left the French player unconscious and knocked two of his teeth out.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Schumacher's action has been described as "one of history's most shocking fouls".
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ball went just wide of the post and Dutch referee Charles Corver deemed Schumacher's tackle on Battiston not to be a foul and awarded a goal kick.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Play was interrupted for several minutes while Battiston, still unconscious and with a broken jaw, was carried off the field on a stretcher.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] After French defender Manuel Amoros had sent a 25-metre drive crashing onto the West German crossbar in the final minute, the match went into extra time.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 92 minutes, France's sweeper Marius Trésor fired a swerving volley under Schumacher's crossbar from ten metres out to make it 2–1.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Six minutes later, an unmarked Alain Giresse drove in an 18-metre shot off the inside of the right post to finish off a counter-attack and put France up 3–1.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the 102nd minute a counter-attack culminated in a cross that recent substitute Karl-Heinz Rummenigge turned in at the near post from a difficult angle with the outside of his foot, reducing France's lead to 3–2.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Then in the 108th minute Germany took a short corner and after France failed to clear, the ball was played by Germany to Littbarski whose cross to Horst Hrubesch was headed back to the centre towards Klaus Fischer, who was unmarked but with his back to goal.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Fischer in turn volleyed the ball past French keeper Jean-Luc Ettori with a bicycle kick, levelling the scores at 3–3.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The resulting penalty shootout was the first at a World Cup finals.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Giresse, Manfred Kaltz, Manuel Amoros, Paul Breitner and Dominique Rocheteau all converted penalties until Uli Stielike was stopped by Ettori, giving France the advantage.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] But then Schumacher stepped forward, lifted the tearful Stielike from the ground, and saved Didier Six's shot.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] With Germany handed the lifeline they needed Littbarski converted his penalty, followed by Platini for France, and then Rummenigge for Germany as the tension mounted.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] France defender Maxime Bossis then had his kick parried by Schumacher who anticipated it, and Hrubesch stepped up to score and send Germany to the World Cup final yet again with a victory on penalties, 5–4.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the match for third place, Poland edged the French side 3–2 which matched Poland's best performance at a World Cup previously achieved in 1974.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] France would go on to win the European Championship two years later.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final, Antonio Cabrini fired a penalty wide of goal in the first half.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the second half, Paolo Rossi scored first for the third straight game by heading home Gentile's bouncing cross at close range.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Exploiting the situation, Italy scored twice more on quick counter-strikes, all the while capitalising on their defence to hold the Germans.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] With Gentile and Gaetano Scirea holding the centre, the Italian strikers were free to counter-punch the weakened German defence.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Marco Tardelli's shot from the edge of the area beat Schumacher first, and Alessandro Altobelli, the substitute for injured striker Francesco Graziani, made it 3–0 at the end of a solo sprint down the right side by the stand-out winger Bruno Conti.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy's lead appeared secure, encouraging Italian president Sandro Pertini to wag his finger at the cameras in a playful "not going to catch us now" gesture.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the 83rd minute, Paul Breitner scored for West Germany, but it was only a consolation goal as Italy won 3–1 to claim their first World Cup title in 44 years, and their third in total.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] By winning, Italy equalled Brazil's record of winning the World Cup three times.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy's total of twelve goals scored in seven matches set a new low for average goals scored per game by a World Cup winning side (subsequently exceeded by Spain in 2010), while Italy's aggregate goal difference of +6 for the tournament remains a record low for a champion, equalled by Spain.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] England became the first and only side in European history to not select a player from that season's European Cup winning team, Aston Villa, in any match.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy's 40-year-old captain-goalkeeper Dino Zoff became the oldest player to win the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the first World Cup in which teams from all six continental confederations participated in the finals, something that did not happen again until 2006.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Seventeen stadiums in fourteen cities hosted the tournament, a record that stood until the 2002 tournament, which was played in twenty stadiums in two countries.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The most used venue was FC Barcelona's Camp Nou stadium, which hosted five matches, including a semi-final; it was the largest stadium used for this tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] With Sarrià Stadium also hosting three matches, Barcelona was the Spanish city with the most matches in España 1982 with eight; Madrid, the nation's capital, followed with seven.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The only new stadium built for this tournament was the Jose Zorrilla stadium in Valladolid.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] This particular World Cup was organised in such a way that all of the matches of each of the six groups were assigned stadiums in cities near to each other, in order to reduce the stress of travel on the players and fans.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group stage matches in the milder northern cities like Bilbao or Gijón would start at 17:00, while the matches in the southern cities like Seville or Valencia would start at 21:00, in an attempt to avoid the intense southern Spanish summer heat.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] When the tournament went into the round-robin second round matches, all the aforementioned cities excluding Barcelona, Alicante and Seville did not host any more matches in España 1982.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Both the Santiago Bernabéu and Vicente Calderón stadiums in Madrid and the Sarrià Stadium in Barcelona were used for the first time for this tournament for the second round matches.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1982 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 24 qualifiers were divided into four groupings which formed the basis of the draw for the group stage.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA announced the six seeded teams on the day of the draw and allocated them in advance to the six groups; as had become standard, the host nation and the reigning champions were among the seeds.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The seeded teams would play all their group matches at the same venue (with the exception of World Cup holders Argentina who would play in the opening game scheduled for the Camp Nou, the largest of the venues).
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The remaining 18 teams were split into three pots based on FIFA's assessment of the team's strength, but also taking in account geographic considerations.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The seedings and group venues for those teams were tentatively agreed at an informal meeting in December 1981 but not officially confirmed until the day of the draw.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA executive Hermann Neuberger told the press that the seeding of England had been challenged by other nations, but they were to be seeded as "the Spanish want England to play in Bilbao for security reasons"*.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 16 January 1982, the draw was conducted at the Palacio de Congresos in Madrid, where the teams were drawn out from the three pots to be placed with the seeded teams in their predetermined groups.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Firstly a draw was made to decide the order in which the three drums containing pots A, B and C would be emptied; this resulted in the order being pot B, C and A.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams were then drawn one-by-one out of the respective pot and entered in the groups in that order.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] A number was then drawn to determine the team's "position" in the group and hence the fixtures.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The only stipulation of the draw was that no group could feature two South American teams.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] As a result, Pot B – which contained two South American teams – was initially drawn with only the four Europeans in the pot.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] These first two European teams drawn from pot B were then to be immediately allocated to Groups 3 and 6 which contained the two South American seeds Argentina and Brazil.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] Once these two groups had been filled with the entrants from Pot B, Chile and Peru would be added to the pot and the draw would continue as normal.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ceremony suffered further embarrassment when one of the revolving drums containing the teams broke down.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The group winners and runners-up advanced to the second round.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The second round of the tournament consisted of four groups of three teams, each played at one stadium in one of Spain's two largest cities: two in Madrid and two in Barcelona.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winners of each group progressed to the semi-finals.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] If the opening game was a draw, the predetermined order of games would proceed as planned.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] These regulations helped ensure that the final group games were of importance as no team could already have progressed to the semi-finals by the end of the second fixtures.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 43,000-capacity Sarria Stadium in Barcelona, used for the Group C round-robin matches between Italy, Argentina and Brazil was, unlike any of the other matches (except 1) in the other groups, severely overcrowded for all three matches.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] Paolo Rossi received the Golden Boot for scoring six goals.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] In total, 146 goals were scored by 100 players, with only one of them credited as own goal.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] The sponsors of the 1982 FIFA World Cup consisted out of 34 FIFA World Cup Sponsors.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot of this World Cup was Naranjito, a male anthropomorphised orange, a typical fruit in Spain, wearing the kit of the host's national team.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was designed by José María Martín and María Dolores Salto from the marketing agency Publicidad Bellido.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] Its name comes from *naranja*, the Spanish word for orange, and the diminutive suffix "-ito".
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match ball for 1982 World Cup, manufactured by Adidas, was the Tango España.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official poster was designed by Joan Miró.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] The final match in group 2 between West Germany and Austria, the "Disgrace of Gijón", was controversial because of accusations of match fixing.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] It led to a rule change so that the final two games in each group were played simultaneously in subsequent World Cups.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] There was some consideration given as to whether England, Northern Ireland, and Scotland would withdraw from the tournament because of the Falklands War between Argentina and the United Kingdom.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] A directive issued by the British sports minister Neil Macfarlane in April, at the start of the conflict, suggested that there should be no contact between British representative teams and Argentina.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] This directive was not rescinded until August, following the end of the tournament and of the hostilities.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] Macfarlane reported to Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher that some players and officials were uneasy about participating because of the casualties suffered by British forces, and the strong diplomatic ties between Argentina and Spain.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA later advised the British Government that there was no prospect that Argentina (the defending champions) would be asked to withdraw, and it also became apparent that no other countries would withdraw from the tournament.
[src:ireland/1982-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was decided by Cabinet Secretary Robert Armstrong to allow the British national teams to participate so that Argentina could not use their absence for propaganda purposes, reversing the intended effect of applying political pressure onto Argentina.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The **1986 FIFA World Cup** was the 13th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] It was played in Mexico from 31 May to 29 June 1986.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The tournament was the second to feature a 24-team format.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombia had been originally chosen to host the competition by FIFA but, largely due to economic reasons, was not able to do so, and resigned in November 1982.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico was selected as the new host in May 1983, and became the first country to host the World Cup more than once, after previously hosting the 1970 edition.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The World Cup was won by Argentina (their second title, after winning in 1978).
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina was captained by the 25-year-old Diego Maradona, who played a large part in his team's success by scoring his "Hand of God" goal, as well as another voted the "Goal of the Century", in the same quarter-final match against England.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] These were two of the five goals that Maradona scored during the tournament, and he also created another five for his teammates.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina beat West Germany 3–2 in the final at Mexico City's Estadio Azteca.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina would not win the World Cup again until 2022, 36 years later.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Total attendance was 2,394,031, an average per match of 46,039.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Canada, Denmark and Iraq made their first appearances at the final stage.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The format of the competition changed from 1982.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The final pair of matches in each group started at the same time and the second round was played on a knockout basis rather than groups.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The 24 teams qualified were divided into six groups of four (A to F).
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The top two teams and the four best third-place finishers from the six groups advanced to the knockout round of 16 teams.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Italy were the defending champions, but were eliminated by France in the round of 16.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The tournament saw the appearance of the Mexican wave, a spectator phenomenon which was popularised worldwide after featuring during the tournament.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombia was originally chosen as hosts by FIFA in June 1974, with Bogotá, Medellín, Cali, Pereira and Bucaramanga intended as the host cities, plus potentially Barranquilla.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombia agreed to host a 16-team competition.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] However, days before the 1978 FIFA World Cup's opening match, FIFA later allowed an expansion to 24 teams for the 1982 World Cup in Spain, which was more challenging for Colombia to host, although FIFA President João Havelange initially gave assurances that they could revert to a 16-team tournament.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Colombian president Julio César Turbay Ayala was initially against holding the tournament in his country, but reluctantly granted permission in October 1980.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] However, the next Colombian president, Belisario Betancur, declared on 5 November 1982 that they could not afford to host the World Cup under the terms that FIFA demanded.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] On 20 May, the committee announced Mexico as the replacement hosts despite Havelange stating that the United States and Canada had made better presentations.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico became the first nation to host two World Cups, as it had hosted the 1970 FIFA World Cup.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Canadian representatives criticised the committee's decision not to consider Canada, saying they had submitted a more complete bid than Mexico, and that they had been misled by the number of stadiums required for bidding.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The United States' bid contained more than the required number of stadiums with the required capacity to host World Cup matches (at least 40,000 capacity, 60,000 for second-round matches and 80,000 for the tournament final).
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico submitted a bid with 14 stadiums, only six of which seated over 40,000 at the time of the bid, and three over 60,000.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Havelange in turn criticised the United States' handling of stadium selection for the football tournament at the 1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Americans also pointed out that Mexico had the influence of two seats on the 22-person executive committee, a FIFA vice president and an executive at Televisa, a Mexican television network with ties to Havelange.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Also working in Mexico's favour was Havelange secretly promising the broadcast rights to Televisa ahead of the vote.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] A severe earthquake in September 1985, eight months before the tournament, cast doubt over Mexico's ability to organise the event, but the stadiums were not affected and it was decided to go ahead with the preparations.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] As 1986 had been declared the International Year of Peace by the United Nations, the advertising boards of all the stadia displayed the FIFA and United Nations logos along with the legend "Football for Peace – Peace Year".
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] For the design of the logo an unofficial motto was adopted: "El Mundo Unido por Un Balón" ("The World United by a Ball").
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The final draw took place on 15 December 1985 hosted at Televisa San Ángel studios in Mexico City.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Three teams qualified for the World Cup for the first time: Canada, Denmark and Iraq.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Iraq played all their 'home' matches on neutral ground in Saudi Arabia because of the Iran–Iraq War.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Canada would not appear again until 2022, and Iraq would not qualify again until the next time the tournament was held in Mexico in 2026.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] South Korea qualified for the first time since 1954, Paraguay for the first time since 1958, Portugal for the first time since 1966, Morocco for the first time since 1970 and Bulgaria and Uruguay for the first time since 1974.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] It remains as of 2026 the last appearance of Hungary and Northern Ireland.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Eleven cities hosted the tournament, with a total of twelve stadiums used (two of them in Mexico City), among which were counted all five stadia that hosted the 1970 tournament.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, the largest stadium used for the tournament, hosted nine matches (including the final), more than any other stadium used.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico City hosted 13 total matches; the Olimpico Universitario Stadium hosted four matches (if the Mexico City suburban town Nezahualcoyotl's three matches are included, this brings the total up to 16 matches; nearly a third of all matches in this tournament).
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The hot, humid and rainy summer weather in Mexico varied from humid desert locations like Monterrey to tropical locations such as Guadalajara; but perhaps the greatest hardship the players had to contend with was the high altitude of the Mexican locations.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico City, the location of the opening and final matches and the location where the most matches were played was 7,380 feet (2,250 m) above sea level and the weather there was not as hot as in other cities used in this World Cup.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] All of these venues except Monterrey were located in central Mexico, as this tournament was organized with the then-standard way of keeping teams playing in locations in close proximity to each other.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] All of the venues listed hosted knockout round matches except the ones in Nezahualcoyotl, Irapuato, Zapopan, Toluca and the Estadio Tecnologico in Monterrey.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1986 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The first round of the finals began in Group A, where Italy were held 1–1 by Bulgaria.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Meanwhile, Argentina beat South Korea 3–1, with Diego Maradona playing a major part.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Italy and Argentina drew 1–1, Maradona and Alessandro Altobelli scoring.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] South Korea and Bulgaria also drew 1–1 in a downpour.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The final set of matches saw Argentina beating Bulgaria 2–0, and Italy narrowly defeating South Korea 3–2.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In Group B Mexico beat Belgium 2–1, and despite being held 1–1 by Paraguay, they won the group after a further win over Iraq, 1–0.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Paraguay and Belgium also progressed after both beating Iraq and drawing with each other.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Group C pitted a strong Dynamo Kyiv-dominated Soviet Union side against the reigning European champions France.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] They drew with each other 1–1, with a goal scored by Vasyl Rats.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] France beat Canada 1–0 and finished in 2nd place in the group after beating Hungary, 3–0.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Hungary had earlier lost 6–0 against the Soviet Union, which won the group due to goal difference.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Group D saw Brazil start against Spain, winning 1–0 after the referee failed to validate a legal goal scored by Míchel.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Northern Ireland began their campaign with a draw against Algeria.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Northern Ireland were then narrowly beaten by Spain before losing to Brazil 3–0 in their final match.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] This match saw a goal from Josimar on his debut and was also the final time Pat Jennings played for Northern Ireland.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Spain qualified along with Brazil after defeating Algeria 3–0.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Denmark stormed through Group E, dubbed the group of death, with a 100 per cent record.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] They beat Alex Ferguson's Scotland 1–0 in their first game, then hammered Uruguay 6–1, with Preben Elkjær hitting a hat-trick.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Denmark beat one of the favourites to win the tournament, West Germany, 2–0 thanks to a Jesper Olsen penalty and a goal from John Eriksen.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] After losing to Denmark, Scotland took the lead against West Germany thanks to a Gordon Strachan goal, but the West Germans fought back to win 2–1.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] After a violent 0–0 draw against Uruguay, the Scots were eliminated from the tournament.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] During that game José Batista of Uruguay was sent off after less than one minute of play for a foul on Strachan, a World Cup record that still stands.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] West Germany went through to the second round despite a loss against Denmark.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Morocco topped Group F after holding both Poland and England to goalless draws, and beating Portugal 3–1.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] By doing so, they became the first African team, and only the second nation from outside Europe and the Americas (after North Korea in 1966), to reach the second round.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In their last first-round game, with the captaincy taken over by Peter Shilton in goal, a first-half Gary Lineker hat-trick helped the reshaped side beat Poland 3–0 – although losing yet another player to a ban for the next round, Terry Fenwick receiving his second booking of the tournament.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Poland had previously beaten Portugal, and in the end the Portuguese were the only team from Group F to be eliminated in the first round.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Portugal, making their first appearance in 20 years, went on strike (in the Saltillo Affair) during the competition.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Players refused to train between their first and second games (against England and Poland) and were eliminated after a loss to Morocco in the final group match.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Belgium beat the Soviet Union 4–3, despite a hat-trick by the Soviets' Igor Belanov.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The game was level at 2–2 after 90 minutes, and in extra time Stephane Demol and Nico Claesen put Belgium 4–2 up.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Belanov scored from the penalty spot with nine minutes remaining, but neither he nor any of his teammates could find a fourth goal for the Soviet Union.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] At the Olympic University Stadium in Mexico City, the European champions France ended Italy's reign as world champions with a 2–0 victory thanks to goals from Michel Platini and Yannick Stopyra.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the rematch of the 1930 FIFA World Cup Final, Argentina just edged out South American champions Uruguay in Puebla thanks to a 42nd-minute strike from Pedro Pasculli.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The all-South American affair had a Diego Maradona goal disallowed.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In Querétaro, Denmark were eliminated as they went from a 1–0 lead to a 5–1 battering against Spain; key player Frank Arnesen was suspended for the game after being sent off against West Germany in their last group match, for taking a swipe at German playmaker Lothar Matthäus.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The Danes scored first, with a Jesper Olsen penalty, but they were then taken apart by a devastating performance from Butragueño of Spain, who scored four of his team's five goals.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] At the Azteca Stadium in Mexico City, England progressed to the quarter-finals comfortably when they saw off Paraguay 3–0, while Brazil brushed aside Poland 4–0.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] West Germany had a much harder time getting past Morocco, for whom goalkeeper Badou Zaki had an outstanding game.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Morocco held out until the 87th minute, when Lothar Matthäus scored the only goal of the match with a free kick.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Mexico won 2–0 against Bulgaria with an outstanding scissor-kick goal by Manuel Negrete which is honored by a remembrance plaque at the Azteca.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the quarter-finals, France faced three-time world champion Brazil in Guadalajara.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Brazil were well on top in the early stages, and Careca put them one up after 18 minutes.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Five minutes before half-time, France drew level when Michel Platini scored his 41st goal after converting a cross from Dominique Rocheteau.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Brazil had a chance to regain the lead in the second half when Branco was fouled by French keeper Joël Bats in the penalty area.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Zico got up to take the kick, but Bats saved Zico's penalty.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The match went to extra time, and France finished slightly the stronger of the two sides.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] No more goals were scored, and so it was time for a penalty shoot-out.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Socrates, who had earlier missed an open goal and headed an easy chance straight into the French keeper's arms, failed with the first kick for Brazil.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The next six penalties were all converted, and then Platini fired over the bar.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Brazil were back on level terms – but not for long.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Julio Cesar struck the post with his penalty, and Luis Fernández then scored to put France through 4–3 on penalties.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Two other quarter-finals were also decided on penalties.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Jan Ceulemans put Belgium ahead against Spain in the 35th minute, but Spanish substitute Señor equalised with five minutes to go.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] No more goals were scored in extra time, and Belgium won the shoot-out 5–4.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] On the hosts' first game outside of the Azteca, Francisco Javier Cruz saw a goal disallowed as West Germany and Mexico drew 0–0 after extra time.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The West Germans eliminated the hosts 4–1 on penalties.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] As a curiosity, the German goalkeeper Harald Schumacher jumped to the right in the three Mexican penalties (stopping two of them).
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The quarter-final between Argentina and England at the Azteca featured two very different goals in the second half by Diego Maradona: the first was scored illegally, as he punched the ball into the goal past England goalkeeper Peter Shilton.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The referee did not see the handball and the goal was given as valid.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] After the game, Maradona claimed the goal was scored "A bit with the head of Maradona and another bit with the hand of God"; it became known as the "Hand of God" goal.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] For his second goal, voted "Goal of the Century" in 2002 on the FIFA website, Maradona dribbled half the length of the field past five English players before scoring.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In Argentina, the game was seen as revenge for the Falklands War.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the first semi-final match, Andreas Brehme put West Germany 1–0 ahead against France in the ninth minute in Guadalajara, but the outcome remained in doubt until two minutes from time when Rudi Völler made it 2–0, and West Germany were in the final for the second World Cup in succession.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In the second semi-final match, Maradona struck twice in the second half as Argentina beat Belgium 2–0 at the Azteca.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] France went on to defeat Belgium in the match for third place, 4–2.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] So it was to be the South American Argentina vs the European West Germany at the final at the Azteca, the second time this massive stadium would host a World Cup Final (the first in 1970).
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Jose Brown put Argentina one up midway through the first half of the final, and when Jorge Valdano scored a second for the South Americans in the 55th minute, Argentina looked to be strolling to victory.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] West Germany then staged a spirited comeback.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Karl-Heinz Rummenigge pulled one back in the 74th minute, and six minutes later Rudi Völler hit the equaliser.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] With seven minutes remaining, a pass from Maradona gave Jorge Burruchaga the chance to score the winner for Argentina.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Eight years on from their home triumph, Argentina regained the world title and 30 million people in Argentina celebrated in the streets after the final victory.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Maradona was the Golden Ball winner as the best player of the tournament, while Gary Lineker of England won the Golden Boot as the leading scorer of the World Cup with six goals.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Argentina beat West Germany for the first time and won their second World Cup.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Belgium finished in fourth place, their best finish in the World Cup until 2018, where they finished third.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Gary Lineker received the Golden Boot for scoring six goals.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] In total, 132 goals were scored by 82 players, with two of them credited as own goals.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The sponsors of the 1986 FIFA World Cup consisted out of 15 FIFA World Cup sponsors.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The official mascot of the 1986 World Cup was *Pique*, a jalapeño pepper, characteristic of Mexican cuisine, with a moustache, a Colimote sombrero, and Mexican football team colours.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] Its name comes from *picante*, a Spanish word meaning "spicy", and was also a pun on the "PK" abbreviation of the football term penalty kick.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The character caused a degree of controversy within Mexico for its ethnic stereotypes.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The official match ball of this World Cup was the "Azteca", manufactured by Adidas.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] It was the first fully synthetic FIFA World Cup ball and the elaborately decorated design was inspired by the hosting nation’s native Aztec architecture and murals.
[src:ireland/1986-fifa-world-cup] The official song of this World Cup was "El mundo unido por un balón".
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The **1990 FIFA World Cup** was the 14th FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial football tournament for men's senior national teams.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It was held from 8 June to 8 July 1990 in Italy, the second country to host the event for a second time (after Mexico in 1986).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams representing 116 national football associations entered and qualification began in April 1988.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Twenty-two teams qualified from this process, along with the host nation Italy and defending champions Argentina.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament was won by West Germany, for the third time.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat defending champions Argentina 1–0 at the Stadio Olimpico in Rome, a rematch of the previous final four years earlier.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy finished third and England fourth, after both lost their semi-finals in penalty shootouts.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Costa Rica, Ireland and the United Arab Emirates made their first appearances in the finals.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the only time the United Arab Emirates qualified for a FIFA World Cup finals.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon went on an unexpectedly strong run in the tournament, becoming the first African team to reach the quarter-finals of the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The official match ball was the Adidas Etrusco Unico.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1990 World Cup is widely regarded as one of the poorest World Cups in terms of the games.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It generated an average 2.21 goals per game – a record low that still stands – and a then-record 16 red cards, including the first dismissal in a final.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, the tournament had a significant lasting influence on the game as a whole.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In England, the team's success in this tournament led to the resurgence of the domestic top-flight, which had suffered from violence on the pitch and hooliganism by spectators throughout the 1980s.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] It saw the introduction of the pre-match Fair Play Flag (then inscribed with "Fair Play Please") to encourage fair play.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Overly defensive tactics of many teams led to the introduction of the back-pass rule in 1992 and three points for a win instead of two, both of which have encouraged attacking play, increasing spectator interest in the sport.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The 1990 World Cup stands as one of the most watched events in television history, garnering an estimated 26.69 billion non-unique viewers over the course of the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This was the first World Cup officially recorded and transmitted in HDTV, which was a joint effort of the Italian broadcaster RAI and Japan's NHK.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The huge success of the broadcasting model also had a lasting impact on the sport.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] At the time, it was the most watched World Cup in history in non-unique viewers, later bettered only by the 1994 and the 2002 editions of the competition.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The vote to choose the hosts of the 1990 tournament was held on 19 May 1984 in Zürich, Switzerland.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Here, the FIFA Executive Committee chose Italy ahead of the only rival bid, the USSR, by 11 votes to 5.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This awarding made Italy only the second nation to host two World Cup tournaments after Mexico had also achieved this with their 1986 staging, having agreed to replace Colombia as hosts the year before the 1990 hosts were chosen.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy had previously held the event in 1934, where they had won their first championship.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Austria, England, France, Greece, West Germany and Yugoslavia also submitted initial applications for the 31 July 1983 deadline.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A month later, only England, Greece, Italy and the Soviet Union remained in the hunt after the other contenders all withdrew.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] All four bids were assessed by FIFA in late 1983, with the final decision over-running into 1984 due to the volume of paperwork involved.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In early 1984, England and Greece also withdrew, leading to a two-horse race in the final vote.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet boycott of the 1984 Olympic Games, announced on the eve of the World Cup decision, was speculated to have been a major factor behind Italy winning the vote so decisively, although this was denied by the FIFA President João Havelange.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Soviet state media responded by accusing FIFA of political corruption, and blamed the organisation's American sponsors (chiefly Coca-Cola) for influencing the decision.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Iran also planned to host the competition.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They proposed it to FIFA in 1977, but a few months later they withdrew their request.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] 116 teams entered the 1990 World Cup, including Italy as host nation and Argentina as reigning World Cup champions, who were both granted automatic qualification.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thus, the remaining 22 finals places were divided among the continental confederations, with 114 initially entering the qualification competition.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Due to rejected entries and withdrawals, 103 teams eventually participated in the qualifying stages.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Thirteen places were contested by UEFA teams (Europe), two by CONMEBOL teams (South America), two by CAF teams (Africa), two by AFC teams (Asia), and two by CONCACAF teams (North and Central America and Caribbean).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The remaining place was decided by a play-off between a CONMEBOL team and a team from the OFC (Oceania).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After finishing in third place in 1986, France missed the tournament for the first time since the 1974 edition.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Mexico was disqualified during the qualification process for fielding four overage players in a prior youth tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three teams made their debuts; this was the first World Cup to feature Costa Rica, the Republic of Ireland, and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Austria, Cameroon, Czechoslovakia and Yugoslavia also returned after missing the 1986 tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As of 2026, this was the only time the United Arab Emirates qualified for the World Cup finals and the last time Mexico did not participate in the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Twelve stadiums in twelve cities were selected to host matches at the 1990 World Cup.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Stadio San Nicola in Bari and Turin's Stadio delle Alpi were completely new venues opened for the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Of the twelve stadiums used, only four (San Siro, Luigi Ferraris, Comunale of Florence, and Renato Dall'Ara) had been used for the 1934 FIFA World Cup, while Trieste was the only host city from 1934 not to be selected for the 1990 tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ten existing venues all underwent extensive programmes of improvements in preparation for the tournament, forcing many of the club tenants of the stadia to move to temporary homes.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Additional seating and roofs were added to most stadia, with further redevelopments seeing running tracks removed and new pitches laid.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Due to structural constraints, several of the existing stadia had to be virtually rebuilt to implement the changes required.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Like España '82 and México '86, the group stage of this tournament was organised so an individual group only played in two cities in close proximity to each other.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group A only played in Rome and Florence (hosts Italy played all but two competitive matches in Rome: their semi-final match was played in Napoli, and their match for third place in Bari), Group B played their matches in Naples and Bari (except for Argentina vs.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon, which was the opening match of the tournament, played in Milan), Group C played their matches in Turin and Genoa, Group D played all their matches in Milan and Bologna, Group E played only in Udine and Verona, and Group F played in the insular cities of Cagliari and Palermo.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The cities that hosted the most World Cup matches were the two biggest cities in Italy: Rome and Milan, each hosting six matches, and Bari, Naples, and Turin each hosted five matches.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cagliari, Udine and Palermo were the only cities of the 12 selected that did not host any knockout round matches.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The England national team, at the British government's request, played all 3 of their group stage matches in Cagliari on the island of Sardinia.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hooliganism, rife in English football in the 1980s had spilled over onto the European continent when 39 mostly Italian Juventus supporters were killed and 600 were injured at the 1985 European Cup Final in Brussels while trying to flee from an attack by Liverpool supporters.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Italian authorities' presence proved to be justified as there were several riots during the time England were playing their matches in Cagliari, leading to a number of injuries, arrests and even deportations.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Most of the construction cost in excess of their original estimates and total costs ended up being over £550 million (approximately $935 million).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Rome's Stadio Olimpico which hosted the final was the most expensive project overall, while Udine's Stadio Friuli, the newest of the existing stadia (opened 14 years prior), cost the least to redevelop.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Squads for the 1990 World Cup consisted of 22 players, as for the previous tournament in 1986.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Replacement of injured players was permitted during the tournament at FIFA's discretion.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two goalkeepers – Argentina's Ángel Comizzo and England's Dave Beasant – entered their respective squads during the tournament to replace injured players (Nery Pumpido and David Seaman).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] 41 match officials from 34 countries were assigned to the tournament to serve as referees and assistant referees.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Officials in italics were only used as assistants during the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Referees dressed only in traditional black jerseys for the final time at a World Cup (a red change shirt was used for two Group C games in which Scotland wore their navy blue shirts).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The six seeded teams for the 1990 tournament were announced on 7 December 1989, two days ahead of the draw.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The FIFA Organising Committee also decided ahead of the draw, to allocate the six seeded teams into the first position of the six groups, in the alphabetic order of their seeding rank: first seed to Group A, second seed to Group B, etc.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The seeds were decided by FIFA, primarily based on the nations' ranked position in the 1986 World Cup (counting double), with the ranked position in the 1982 World Cup also considered as a secondary influence (counting normal).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Six of the final eight in 1986 had qualified for the 1990 tournament, the missing nations being Mexico (quarter-final in 1986) and France (third place).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Italy did not reach the final eight in 1986, but despite this were still seeded first in 1990 as hosts.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In total, the primary seeding criteria hereby resulted in seven countries to be potentially seeded.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As the tournament structure only had place for the selection of six seeded teams, this left FIFA needing to exclude one of the six teams qualifying for a seed based on the primary sporting criteria.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA first decided, that all qualified teams having played the 1986 semi-finals (Argentina, Germany, Belgium), should be guaranteed a seeding place behind the first seeded host nation Italy.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Consequently, one of the three qualified nations who were eliminated in the 1986 quarter-finals (Brazil, England or Spain), should not be seeded based on the secondary sporting criteria - looking at their 1982 FIFA World Cup results.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Owing to their performance in 1982, but also to their overall World Cup record, Brazil were seeded third, and not considered to drop out of the seedings.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA therefore had to choose if England or Spain should be granted the last seeding slot, and ultimately opted to seed England ahead of Spain.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spain had only been eliminated in their 1986 quarter-final on penalties, albeit by fourth-placed Belgium, while England had been defeated in their 1986 quarter-final after 90 minutes by eventual winners Argentina.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If the only criteria had been the 1986 ranking, then Spain should have been seeded as #6 instead of England; a viewpoint being supported by FIFA President João Havelange as late as 29 November 1989.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If taking the 1982 ranking into consideration, England however had performed slightly better than Spain - as they had finished ahead of them in Group B of the second group stage.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] If only considering the results of the 1978 event, it could on the other hand have been counter argued, that Spain by their group stage performance and Netherlands by their silver medal accomplishment, should have been seeded rather than England and Belgium who both had failed to qualify.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Spanish officials believed the seeding was contrived to ensure England would be placed in Group F, the group to be held off the Italian mainland, in a bid to contain England's hooliganism problems.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their coach Luis Suárez said, "We feel we've been cheated...they wanted to seed England and to send it to Cagliari at all costs.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] FIFA countered that "the formula was based on the teams' respective showings during the previous two World Cups.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This is in no way a concession to English hooliganism".
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, this argument was countered by the fact that Netherlands had themselves failed to qualify for both the 1982 and 1986 World Cups, which was considered the most important factor in the decision not to seed them.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the group stage had been completed, England could be said to have justified their seeded position by winning their Group F ahead of Ireland and Netherlands; while Spain seemed to have made their own point about being worth a seeded position, by defeating Belgium to top their own Group E.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] On 9 December 1989, the draw was conducted at the Palazzo dello Sport in Rome, where the teams were drawn out from the three pots to be placed with the seeded teams in their predetermined groups, in alphabetic order.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A special draw decided teams should first be drawn from Pot 1, then from Pot 3, and finally from Pot 2.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each drawn team also had their group position number drawn from a separate group bowl, in order to decide their exact match schedule.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The procedure for the draw, was presented by FIFA at a press meeting the day before the draw.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] However, after having received objections from Italian officials, FIFA opted to slightly change their special Pot 2 rule, during the last 24 hours ahead of the draw.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] When FIFA accepted to change the Pot 2 rule into the final version presented at the televised draw, this lowered the chance for the Italian Group A to draw a South American Pot 2 team, from the 80% chance created by the initial wording to only a 33% chance (two out of six teams).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The ceremony was hosted by Italian television presenter Pippo Baudo, with Italian actress Sophia Loren and opera singer Luciano Pavarotti conducting the draw alongside FIFA general secretary Sepp Blatter.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The event also featured the official mascot of this World Cup, *Ciao*, a stick figure player with a football head and an Italian tricolour body that formed the word "ITALIA" when deconstructed and reconstructed.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In each group, the teams would play three matches, one against each of the other teams.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Victories would be granted 2 points, while a draw awarded 1 point.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After completion of the group stage, the best two teams of each group as well as the four best ranked third places, advanced to round 16 in the knockout stage.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] This format was identical with the tournament structure being used in 1986.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A total of 52 games would be played, including the final and a match for third place between the two semi-final losers.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The tournament generated a record low goals-per-game average and a then-record of 16 red cards were handed out.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the knockout stage, many teams played defensively for 120 minutes, with the intention of trying their luck in the penalty shoot-out, rather than risk going forward.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Two exceptions were the eventual champions West Germany and hosts Italy, the only teams to win three of their four knockout matches in normal time.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] There were four penalty shoot-outs, a record equalled with the 2006, 2014, and 2018 tournaments, until it was surpassed by the 2022 tournament, with five.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Eight matches went to extra time, also a record tied with the 2014 tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Losing finalists Argentina were prime examples of this trend of cautious defensive play, choosing to do so because 3 of their best players were left off the squad due to injury.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They scored only five goals in the entire tournament (a record low for a finalist).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina also became the first team to advance twice on penalty shoot-outs and the first team to fail to score and have a player sent off in a World Cup final.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Largely as a result of this trend IFAB introduced the back-pass rule in time for the 1994 tournament to make it harder for teams to time-waste by repeatedly passing the ball back for their goalkeepers to pick up.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Three, rather than two points would be awarded for victories at future tournaments to help further encourage attacking play.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon reached the quarter-finals, where they were narrowly defeated by England.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They opened the tournament with a shock victory over reigning champions Argentina, before topping the group ahead of them, Romania and European Championship runners-up the Soviet Union.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their success was fired by the goals of Roger Milla, a 38-year-old forward who came out of international retirement to join the national squad at the last moment after a personal request from Cameroonian President Paul Biya.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Milla's four goals and flamboyant goal celebrations made him one of the tournament's biggest stars as well as taking Cameroon to the last eight.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Most of Cameroon's squad was made up of players who played in France's premier football league, Ligue 1 - French is one of the officially spoken languages in Cameroon, it being a former French territory.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In reaching this stage, they had gone further than any African nation had managed in a World Cup before; a feat not surpassed until Morocco reached the semi-final in 2022.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon's feat (equalled by Senegal in 2002 and Ghana in 2010) remains the best by a Sub-Saharan African team.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Their success was African football's biggest yet on the world stage and FIFA subsequently decided to allocate the CAF qualifying zone an additional place for the next World Cup tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite the performances of nations such as Cameroon, Colombia, Ireland, Romania and Costa Rica, the semi-finalists consisted of Argentina, England, Italy and West Germany, all previous World Cup winners, with eight previous titles between them.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the 1970 tournament, this is only the second time in the history of the World Cup this has occurred.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams which finished first, second and third had also contested both the two previous World Cup Finals between themselves.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Group stage saw the twenty-four teams divided into six groups of four teams.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Each group was a round-robin of six games, in which each team played one match against each of the other teams in the same group.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Teams were awarded two points for a win, one point for a draw and none for a defeat.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The teams coming first and second in each group qualified for the Round of 16.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The four best third-placed teams would also advance to the next stage.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] As was typical of a World Cup staged in Europe, the matches all started at either 5:00 or 9:00 in the evening; this allowed for the games to avoid being played in the heat of an Italian summer, which would soar past 86F (30C) all over Italy.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Hosts Italy won Group A with a 100 percent record.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They beat Austria 1–0 thanks to substitute Salvatore 'Totò' Schillaci, who had played only one international before but would become a star during the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] A second 1–0 victory followed against a United States team already thumped 5–1 by Czechoslovakia.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Czechoslovaks ended runners-up in the group, while the USA's first appearance in a World Cup Finals since 1950 ended with three consecutive defeats.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon defeated world champions Argentina 1–0.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Despite ending the match with only nine men, the African team held on for a shock 1–0 win, with contrasting fortunes for the Biyik brothers: François Omam-Biyik scoring the winning goal with a downward header, shortly after seeing André Kana-Biyik sent off for a serious foul.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Cameroon's second red card was awarded to Benjamin Massing for up-ending Caniggia in the last few minutes as Argentina pressed for an equalizer.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In Cameroon's second game, the introduction of Roger Milla was the catalyst for a 2–1 win over Romania, Milla scoring twice from the bench (making him the oldest goalscorer in the tournament).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] With progression assured, Cameroon slumped to a 4–0 defeat in their final group game to the Soviet Union (in what would be their last World Cup due to the dissolution of the Soviet Union), who were striving to stay in the tournament on goal difference after successive 2–0 defeats.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Argentina lost their veteran goalkeeper, Nery Pumpido, to a broken leg during their victory over the USSR: his replacement, Sergio Goycochea, proved to be one of the stars of their tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the final match, a 1–1 draw between Romania and Argentina sent both through, equal on points and on goal difference but with Romania having the advantage on goals scored; Romania were thus second, and Argentina qualified as one of the best third-placed teams.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Costa Rica beat Scotland 1–0 in their first match, lost 1–0 to Brazil in their second, then saw off Sweden 2–1 to claim a place in the second round.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Brazil took maximum points from the group.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] They began with a 2–1 win over Sweden, then beat both Costa Rica and Scotland 1–0.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Scotland's 2–1 win over Sweden was not enough to save them from an early return home as one of the two lowest-ranked third-placed teams.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group D featured the most goals of all the groups, most due to two large wins of West Germany and defensive inadequacies of a United Arab Emirates team that lost 2–0 to Colombia, 5–1 to West Germany and 4–1 to Yugoslavia.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The West Germans topped the group after a 4–1 opening victory over group runners-up Yugoslavia.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The winners of Group E were Spain, for whom Míchel hit a hat-trick as they beat South Korea 3–1 in an unbeaten group campaign.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Belgium won their first two games against South Korea and Uruguay to ensure their progress; Uruguay's advance to the second round came with an injury-time winner against South Korea to edge them through as the weakest of the third-placed sides to remain in the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Group F featured the Netherlands, England, the Republic of Ireland and Egypt.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] In the six group games, no team managed to score more than once in a match.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England beat Egypt 1–0—the only match with a decisive result—and that was enough to win the group.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England took the lead with an early goal for Lineker against Ireland, but Sheedy's late equaliser secured a draw.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] The Netherlands drew with Egypt: they had taken a 1–0 lead, but Egypt equalised with a penalty by Abdelghani.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] England then drew 0–0 with the Netherlands; a goal from a free-kick by Pearce was disallowed.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] For the second World Cup in succession, however, England lost their captain Bryan Robson to an injury which put him out of the tournament, just over halfway through their second match.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Ireland missed a number of scoring opportunities in the second half of the other 0–0 draw against Egypt.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] After the first four matches all four teams had equal records with two draws, one goal for and one goal against.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Both teams qualified, but they had to draw lots to place the teams in second and third place.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p01] Rules for classification: 1) Points; 2) Goal difference; 3) Goals scored; 4) Drawing of lots (if deciding qualification).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The knockout stage involved the 16 teams that qualified from the group stage of the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were four rounds of matches, with each round eliminating half of the teams entering that round.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The successive rounds were: round of 16, quarter-finals, semi-finals and the final.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Scores after extra time are indicated by (a.e.t.) and penalty shoot-outs are indicated by (pen.).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Two of the ties—Brazil vs Argentina and Italy vs Uruguay—pitted former champion countries against each other and West Germany met the Netherlands in a rematch of the 1974 World Cup Final.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The all-South American game was won for Argentina by a goal from Claudio Caniggia with 10 minutes remaining after a run through the Brazilian defence by Diego Maradona and a strong performance from their goalkeeper Sergio Goycochea.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It would later come to light that Branco had been offered water spiked with tranquillisers by Maradona and Ricardo Giusti during half time, to slow him down in the second half.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Initially discredited by the press, Branco would be publicly proven right years later, when Maradona confessed the episode on a TV show in Argentina.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Hosts Italy beat Uruguay 2–0, thanks to goals from Schillaci and Aldo Serena.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match between West Germany and the Netherlands was held in Milan, and both sides featured players from the two Milanese clubs (Germans Andreas Brehme, Lothar Matthäus and Jürgen Klinsmann for Internazionale, and Dutchmen Marco van Basten, Ruud Gullit and Frank Rijkaard for Milan).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] After 22 minutes Rudi Völler and Rijkaard were both dismissed after a number of incidents between the two players, including Rijkaard spitting on Völler.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] As the players walked off the pitch together, Rijkaard spat on Völler a second time.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Early in the second half, Jürgen Klinsmann put the West Germans ahead and Andreas Brehme added a second with eight minutes left.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A Ronald Koeman penalty for the Netherlands in the 89th minute narrowed the score to 2–1 but the Germans saw the game out to gain some revenge for their exit to the Dutch in the previous European Championship.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Colombia, Roger Milla was introduced as a second-half substitute with the game goalless, eventually breaking the deadlock midway in extra time.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Three minutes later he netted a second after Colombian goalkeeper, René Higuita was dispossessed by Milla while well out of his goal, leaving the striker free to slot the ball into the empty net.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Though the deficit was soon reduced to 2–1, Cameroon held on to become the first African team to reach the World Cup quarter-finals.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Costa Rica were beaten 4–1 by Czechoslovakia, for whom Tomáš Skuhravý scored the tournament's second and final hat-trick.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Republic of Ireland's match with Romania remained goalless after extra time and the Irish side won 5–4 on penalties.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] David O'Leary converted the penalty that clinched Ireland's place in the quarter-finals.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Ireland thus became the first team since Sweden in 1938 to reach the last eight in a World Cup finals tournament without winning a match outright.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Yugoslavia beat Spain 2–1 after extra time, with Dragan Stojković scoring both the Yugoslavs' goals.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England were the final qualifier against Belgium, as midfielder David Platt's swivelling volley broke the stalemate with the game moments away from a penalty shoot-out.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The first game of the last 8 saw Argentina and a Yugoslav side, reduced to 10 men after only half an hour, play out a goalless stalemate.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The holders reached the semi-finals after winning the penalty shoot-out 3–2, despite Maradona having his penalty saved.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A second Argentine miss (by Pedro Troglio) looked to have eliminated them until goalkeeper Sergio Goycochea – playing because first choice Nery Pumpido broke his leg during the group stage – rescued his side by stopping the Yugoslavs' final two spotkicks.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The Republic of Ireland's World Cup run was brought to an end by a single goal from Schillaci in the first half of their quarter-final with hosts Italy, thus becoming the team who advanced the furthest in a World Cup without winning a single match.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] West Germany beat Czechoslovakia with a 25th minute Lothar Matthäus penalty.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The quarter-final between England and Cameroon was the only quarter-final to produce more than one goal.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Despite Cameroon's heroics earlier in the tournament, David Platt put England ahead in the 25th minute.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the second half, the game was turned on its head during a five-minute stretch: first Cameroon were awarded a penalty from which Emmanuel Kunde scored the equaliser; then in the 65th minute Eugene Ekeke put Cameroon ahead.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Cameroon came within eight minutes of reaching the semi-finals before they conceded a penalty, which Gary Lineker converted.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Midway through extra time, England were awarded another penalty and Lineker again scored from the spot.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England were through to the semi-finals for the first time since 1966.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The first semi-final featured the host nation, Italy, and the world champions, Argentina in Naples.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] 'Toto' Schillaci scored yet again to put Italy ahead in the 17th minute, but Claudio Caniggia equalised midway through the second half, breaking Walter Zenga's clean sheet streak throughout the tournament.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] There were no more goals in the 90 minutes or in extra time despite Maradona (who played for Naples in Serie A at the time) showing glimpses of magic, but there was a sending-off: Ricardo Giusti of Argentina was shown the red card in the 13th minute of extra time.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentina went through on penalties, winning the shoot-out 4–3 after more heroics from Goycochea.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The semi-final between West Germany and England at Juventus' home stadium in Turin was goalless at half-time.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Then, in the 60th minute, a free-kick tapped to Andreas Brehme resulted in a shot which was deflected off Paul Parker into his own net.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England equalised with ten minutes left; Gary Lineker was the scorer, Parker somewhat redeeming himself by providing the assist.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Klinsmann was guilty of two glaring misses and both sides struck a post.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England had another Platt goal disallowed for offside.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The match went to penalties, and West Germany went on to win the shoot-out 4–3, Pearce having his penalty saved and Waddle firing over the bar.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The two matches had the exact same score at 1–1, an identical penalty shootout score at 4–3, and the same order of penalties scored.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The game saw three goals in a 15-minute spell near the end of the match.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Roberto Baggio opened the scoring after a mistake by England's goalkeeper Peter Shilton, in his final game before international retirement, presented a simple opportunity.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] A header by David Platt levelled the game 10 minutes later but Schillaci was fouled in the penalty area five minutes later, leading to a penalty.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Schillaci himself got up to convert the kick to win him the tournament's Golden Boot for his six-goal tally.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Nicola Berti had a goal ruled out minutes later, but the hosts claimed third place.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] England had the consolation prize of the Fair Play award, having received no red cards and the lowest average number of yellows per match.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The final between West Germany and Argentina has been cited as one of two most cynical and lowest-quality of all World Cup Finals, next to the 2010, between Spain and Netherlands.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the 65th minute, Argentina's Pedro Monzon – himself only recently on as a substitute – was sent off for a foul on Jürgen Klinsmann.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Monzon was the first player sent off in a World Cup Final.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Argentina, weakened by suspension and injury, offered little attacking threat throughout a contest dominated by the West Germans, who struggled to create many clear goalscoring opportunities.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The only goal of the contest arrived in the 85th minute when Mexican referee Edgardo Codesal awarded a penalty to West Germany, after a foul on Rudi Völler by Roberto Sensini leading to Argentinian protests.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] An earlier possible foul by Goycoecha, who tripped Klaus Augenthaler in the box, had not been given.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] German commentators speculated, that the subsequent penalty was therefore a concession by the referee.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Andreas Brehme converted the spot kick to settle the contest.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In the closing moments, Argentina were reduced to nine after Gustavo Dezotti, who had already been given a yellow card earlier in the match, received a red card when he hauled Jürgen Kohler to the ground during a stoppage in play.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The 1–0 scoreline provided another first: Argentina were the first team to fail to score in a World Cup Final.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] With its third title (and three second-place finishes) West Germany – in its final tournament before national reunification – became the most successful World Cup nation at the time along with Italy and Brazil (who had also won three titles each then).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] West German manager Franz Beckenbauer became the first man to both captain (in 1974) and manage a World Cup winning team, and only the second man (after Mário Zagallo of Brazil) to win the World Cup as a player and as team manager.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was also the first time a team from UEFA won the final against a non-European team.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] Salvatore Schillaci received the Golden Boot award for scoring six goals in the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] This made him the second Italian footballer to have this honour, after Paolo Rossi won the award in 1982.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In total, 115 goals were scored by 75 players (none credited as own goals).
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] FIFA published the first All-Star Team in 1938, but it never made an All-Star Team again until 1990 due to ensuing complaints.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] In 1990 an All-Star Team was announced in combination with the Golden Ball ceremony.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] It was chosen by the same journalists who chose the best player, but this team is still considered unofficial.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] After the tournament, FIFA published a ranking of all teams that competed in the 1990 World Cup finals based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The sponsors of the 1990 FIFA World Cup are divided into two categories: FIFA World Cup Sponsors and Italy Supporters.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official mascot of this World Cup was "Ciao", a stick figure player with a football head and an Italian tricolore body.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official match ball of this World Cup was the "Etrusco Unico", manufactured by Adidas.
[src:ireland/1990-fifa-world-cup-p02] The official song of this World Cup was "Un'estate italiana".
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The **1991 Rugby World Cup** (French: *Coupe du monde de rugby 1991*) was the second edition of the Rugby World Cup, and was jointly hosted by England, Scotland, Wales, Ireland and France: at the time, the five European countries who participated in the Five Nations Championship.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] This was the first Rugby World Cup to be staged in the northern hemisphere, with England the hosts of the final.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Also for the first time, qualifying competitions were introduced as the number of entrants had increased, from 16 nations four years earlier, to 33 countries.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The eight quarter-finalists from 1987 qualified automatically with the remaining eight spots contested through qualifiers by 25 countries.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] This resulted in only one new side qualifying for the tournament, Western Samoa replacing Tonga.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The same 16-team pool/knock-out format was used with just minor changes to the points system.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] South Africa was again not included because of sanctions imposed on the country by the International Rugby Board (IRB), due to the government's apartheid policies.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The pool stages produced a major upset when Western Samoa, who were making their debut in the tournament, defeated the 1987 semi-finalists Wales 16–13 in Cardiff.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Along with the other results in the group, this led to the elimination of Wales, who finished third in Pool 3.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Also notable in pool play was that Canada finished second in their pool to qualify for the quarter-finals, which remains their best performance in the World Cup.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Fiji, as quarter-finalists four years earlier, had expected to occupy that position, but after the upset loss to Canada and a hammering by France, they lost even their final match against the unfancied Romanian team.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Earlier, the opening match had pitted the holders New Zealand against the hosts England: New Zealand overturned a narrow half-time deficit to win the match and the pool, both teams qualifying for the quarter-finals with easy victories in their other matches.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Scotland beat Ireland to top their pool, again both teams qualifying.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] In the quarter-finals, neither Canada nor Western Samoa proved a match for New Zealand or Scotland, respectively.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Meanwhile, England knocked out 1987 finalist France in a bruising encounter.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Australia pipped Ireland 19–18 in a thrilling match at Lansdowne Road, with a last-gasp try from fly-half Michael Lynagh coming after the Irish took an unexpected 18–15 lead.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The semi-finals produced two tight matches: England overcame Scotland 9–6, a late drop goal deciding a tryless match in a torrential downpour at Murrayfield Stadium, and Australia defeated the defending champions New Zealand 16–6 at Lansdowne Road.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The final was played at Twickenham Stadium in London, and saw Australia win 12–6 against England, with a first-half try from prop Tony Daly.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The following 16 teams, shown by region, qualified for the 1991 Rugby World Cup.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Of the 16 teams, eight of those places were automatically filled by quarter-finalists from the 1987 World Cup and did not have to play any qualification matches.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] 25 nations competed in a qualification process designed to fill the remaining eight spots, bringing the total participation to 33 nations.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] In the event, there was only one change from the 1987 tournament, with Western Samoa appearing in place of Tonga.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] As in the 1987 Rugby World Cup the 16 nations were divided into four pools of four nations, with each nation playing their other pool opponents once, every nation playing three times during the pool stages.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] Nations were awarded 2 points for a win, 1 for a draw and zero for a loss, the top two nations of every pool advanced to the quarter-finals.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The runners-up of each pool faced the winners of a different pool in the quarter-finals.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The winners moved on to the semi-finals, with the winners then moving onto the final, and the losers of the semi-finals contesting a third/fourth place play off.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] A total of 32 matches (24 in the pool stage and eight in the knock-out stage) were played throughout the tournament over 30 days from 3 October 1991 to 2 November 1991.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The tournament's top point scorer was Ireland's Ralph Keyes, who scored 68 points.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] David Campese and Jean-Baptiste Lafond scored the most tries, six in total.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] The event was broadcast in the United Kingdom by ITV who took over the rights from the BBC.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] 13 million people in the United Kingdom watched the final.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] In Australia it was the second and the last (as of the 2023 tournament) Rugby World Cup to be broadcast on ABC television as, from 1995, the commercial networks 7, 9 and 10 would all take over the broadcast rights sometimes in partnership with pay and streaming broadcasters Fox and Stan.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] In New Zealand, it was broadcast by TVNZ.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] In France, it was broadcast by TF1 instead of France's traditional Rugby broadcasters Antenne2.
[src:ireland/1991-rugby-world-cup] ITV, TF1 and RTE were the host broadcasters broadcasting the pictures around the world as well to their own countries.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The geography of Ireland comprises relatively low-lying mountains surrounding a central plain, with several navigable rivers extending inland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Much of Ireland was woodland until the end of the Middle Ages.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Today, woodland makes up about 10% of the island, compared with a European average of over 33%, with most of it being non-native conifer plantations.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Its lush vegetation is a product of its mild climate, which is influenced by the Atlantic Ocean and thus very moderate, and winters are milder than expected for such a northerly area, although summers are cooler than those in continental Europe.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Gaelic Ireland had emerged by the 1st century AD.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The island was Christianised from the 5th century onwards.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] During this period Ireland was divided amongst petty kings, who in turn served under the kings of the traditional provinces (*Cúige*; lit.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] 'fifth') vying for dominance and the title of High King of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Between the late 8th and early 11th centuries, Viking raids and settlement took place culminating in the Battle of Clontarf on 23 April 1014 which resulted in the end of Viking power in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Following the 12th-century Anglo-Norman invasion, England claimed sovereignty.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] However, English rule did not extend over the whole island until the 16th–17th century Tudor conquest, which led to colonisation by settlers from Britain.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In the 1690s, a system of Protestant English rule was designed to materially disadvantage the Catholic majority and Protestant dissenters, and was extended during the 18th century.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] With the Acts of Union in 1801, Ireland became a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Great Famine of the 1840s saw the population fall by over 20%, through death and emigration.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Northern Ireland saw much civil unrest from the late 1960s until the 1990s.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This subsided following the Good Friday Agreement in 1998.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1973, both the Republic of Ireland and the United Kingdom, with Northern Ireland as part of it, joined the European Economic Community.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Following a referendum vote in 2016, the United Kingdom, Northern Ireland included, left the European Union (EU) in 2020.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Northern Ireland was granted a limited special status and allowed to operate within the EU single market for goods without being in the European Union.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Irish culture has had a significant influence on other cultures, especially in the field of literature.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Alongside mainstream Western culture, a strong indigenous culture exists, as expressed through Gaelic games, Irish music, Irish language, and Irish dance.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The island's culture shares many features with that of Great Britain, including the English language, and sports such as association football, rugby, horse racing, golf, and boxing.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The names *Ireland* and *Éire* both derive from Old Irish *Ériu*, which in turn comes from Proto-Celtic *ɸīweriyū* meaning "fertile soil".
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Classical Latin name for the island of Ireland, *Ivernia*, also comes from this same root, and it remains a popular, poetic synonym for the island (usually respelt "*Hibernia*", under the influence of *hibernum*, the Latin word for "winter").
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] During the last glacial period, and until about 16,000 BC, much of Ireland was periodically covered in ice.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The relative sea level was less than 50 m lower resulting in an ice bridge (but not a land bridge) forming between Ireland and Great Britain.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] By 14,000 BC this ice bridge existed only between Northern Ireland and Scotland and by 12,000 BC Ireland was completely separated from Great Britain.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Later, around 6,100 BC, Great Britain became separated from continental Europe.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Until recently, the earliest evidence of human activity in Ireland was dated at 12,500 years ago, demonstrated by a butchered bear bone found in a cave in County Clare.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 2021, a reindeer bone with chop marks, which had been found in Castlepook Cave near Doneraile, County Cork in the early twentieth century during Richard J.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ussher's excavations, was dated to 33,000 years ago by Dr Ruth Carden, a paleozoologist from the School of Archaeology in University College Dublin, pushing back the earliest signs of human activity by 20,000 years.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] By about 8,000 BC, more sustained occupation of the island has been shown, with evidence for Mesolithic communities around the island.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Some time before 4,000 BC, Neolithic settlers introduced cereal cultivars, domesticated animals such as cattle and sheep, built large timber buildings, and stone monuments.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The earliest evidence for farming in Ireland or Great Britain is from Ferriter's Cove, County Kerry, where a flint knife, cattle bones and a sheep's tooth were carbon-dated to c.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Field systems were developed in different parts of Ireland, including at the *Céide Fields*, that has been preserved beneath a blanket of peat in present-day Tyrawley in northwest Mayo.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] An extensive field system, arguably the oldest in the world, consisted of small divisions separated by dry-stone walls.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The fields were farmed for several centuries between 3,500 BC and 3,000 BC.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Wheat and barley were the principal crops.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] How and when the island became Celtic has been debated for close to a century, with the migrations of the Celts being one of the more enduring themes of archaeological and linguistic studies.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The most recent genetic research strongly associates the spread of Indo-European languages (including Celtic) through Western Europe with a people bringing a composite Bell Beaker culture, with its arrival in Britain and Ireland dated to around the middle of the third millennium BC.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Koch and others, Ireland in the Late Bronze Age was part of a maritime trading culture called the Atlantic Bronze Age that also included Britain, western France and Iberia, and that this is where Celtic languages developed.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This contrasts with the traditional view that their origin lies in mainland Europe with the Hallstatt culture.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The long-standing traditional view is that the Celtic language, Ogham script and culture were brought to Ireland by waves of invading or migrating Celts from mainland Europe.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This theory draws on the *Lebor Gabála Érenn*, a medieval Christian pseudo-history of Ireland, along with the presence of Celtic culture, language and artefacts found in Ireland such as Celtic bronze spears, shields, torcs and other finely crafted Celtic associated possessions.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The theory holds that there were four separate Celtic invasions of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Priteni were said to be the first, followed by the Belgae from northern Gaul and Britain.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Later, Laighin tribes from Armorica were said to have invaded Ireland and Britain more or less simultaneously.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Lastly, the Milesians (Gaels) were said to have reached Ireland from either northern Iberia or southern Gaul.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] It was claimed that a second wave named the Euerni, belonging to the Belgae people of northern Gaul, began arriving about the 6th century BC.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] They were said to have given their name to the island.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The theory was advanced in part because of the lack of archaeological evidence for large-scale Celtic immigration, though it is accepted that such movements are notoriously difficult to identify.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Historical linguists are skeptical that this method alone could account for the absorption of Celtic language, with some saying that an assumed processual view of Celtic linguistic formation is 'an especially hazardous exercise'.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Genetic lineage investigation into the area of Celtic migration to Ireland has led to findings that showed no significant differences in mitochondrial DNA between Ireland and large areas of continental Europe, in contrast to parts of the Y-chromosome pattern.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] When taking both into account, a study concluded that modern Celtic speakers in Ireland could be thought of as European "Atlantic Celts" showing a shared ancestry throughout the Atlantic zone from northern Iberia to western Scandinavia rather than substantially central European.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 2012, research showed that the occurrence of genetic markers for the earliest farmers was almost eliminated by Beaker-culture immigrants: they carried what was then a new Y-chromosome R1b marker, believed to have originated in Iberia about 2,500 BC.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The prevalence amongst modern Irish men of this mutation is a remarkable 84%, the highest in the world, and closely matched in other populations along the Atlantic fringes down to Spain.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A similar genetic replacement happened with lineages in mitochondrial DNA.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The earliest written records of Ireland come from classical Greco-Roman geographers.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ptolemy in his *Almagest* refers to Ireland as *Mikra Brettania* ("Little Britain"), in contrast to the larger island which he called *Megale Brettania* ("Great Britain").
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In his map of Ireland in his later work, *Geography*, Ptolemy refers to Ireland as *Iouernia* and to Great Britain as *Albion*.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] These names were likely to have been the local names for the islands at the time.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The earlier names, in contrast, were likely to have been coined before direct contact with local peoples was made.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Romans referred to Ireland by its Latinised name, *Hibernia*, and later also used the term Scotia.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ptolemy records 16 nations inhabiting every part of Ireland in 100 AD.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The relationship between the Roman Empire and the kingdoms of ancient Ireland is unclear.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] However, finds of Roman coins have been made, for example at the Iron Age settlement of Freestone Hill near Gowran and Newgrange.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ireland continued as a patchwork of rival kingdoms; however, beginning in the 7th century, a concept of national kingship gradually became articulated through the concept of a High King of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] All of the Irish kingdoms had their own kings but were nominally subject to the high king.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The high king was drawn from the ranks of the provincial kings and ruled also the royal kingdom of Meath, with a ceremonial capital at the Hill of Tara.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The concept did not become a political reality until the Viking Age and even then was not a consistent one.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ireland did have a culturally unifying rule of law: the early written judicial system, the Brehon Laws, administered by a professional class of jurists known as the *brehons*.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The arts of manuscript illumination, metalworking and sculpture flourished and produced treasures such as the *Book of Kells*, ornate jewellery and the many carved stone crosses that still dot the island today.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A mission founded in 563 on Iona by the Irish monk Saint Columba began a tradition of Irish missionary work that spread Celtic Christianity and learning to Scotland, England and the Frankish Empire on continental Europe after the fall of Rome.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] These missions continued until the late Middle Ages, establishing monasteries and centres of learning, producing scholars such as Sedulius Scottus and Johannes Eriugena and exerting much influence in Europe.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] From the 9th century, waves of Viking raiders plundered Irish monasteries and towns.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] These raids added to a pattern of raiding and endemic warfare that was already deep-seated in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Vikings were involved in establishing most of the major coastal settlements in Ireland: Dublin, Limerick, Cork, Wexford, Waterford, as well as other smaller settlements.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] On 1 May 1169, an expedition of Cambro-Norman knights, with an army of about 600 men, landed at Bannow Strand in present-day County Wexford.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] It was led by Richard de Clare, known as 'Strongbow' owing to his prowess as an archer.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The invasion, which coincided with a period of renewed Norman expansion, was at the invitation of Dermot Mac Murrough, King of Leinster.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1166, Mac Murrough had fled to Anjou, France, following a war involving Tighearnán Ua Ruairc, of Breifne, and sought the assistance of the Angevin King Henry II, in recapturing his kingdom.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1171, Henry arrived in Ireland in order to review the general progress of the expedition.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] He wanted to re-exert royal authority over the invasion which was expanding beyond his control.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Henry successfully re-imposed his authority over Strongbow and the Cambro-Norman warlords and persuaded many of the Irish kings to accept him as their overlord, an arrangement confirmed in the 1175 Treaty of Windsor.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The invasion was legitimised by reference to provisions of the alleged Papal Bull *Laudabiliter*, issued by an Englishman, Adrian IV, in 1155.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The document apparently encouraged Henry to take control in Ireland in order to oversee the financial and administrative reorganisation of the Irish Church and its integration into the Roman Church system.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Some restructuring had already begun at the ecclesiastical level following the Synod of Kells in 1152.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] There has been significant controversy regarding the authenticity of *Laudabiliter*, and there is no general agreement as to whether the bull was genuine or a forgery.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Further, it had no standing in the Irish legal system.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1172, Pope Alexander III further encouraged Henry to advance the integration of the Irish Church with Rome.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Henry was authorised to impose a tithe of one penny per hearth as an annual contribution.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This church levy, called Peter's Pence, is extant in Ireland as a voluntary donation.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In turn, Henry assumed the title of Lord of Ireland which Henry conferred on his younger son, John Lackland, in 1185.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This defined the Anglo-Norman administration in Ireland as the Lordship of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] When Henry's successor, Richard the Lionheart died unexpectedly in 1199, John inherited the crown of England and retained the Lordship of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Over the century that followed, Norman feudal law gradually replaced the Gaelic Brehon Law across large areas, so that by the late 13th century the Norman-Irish had established a feudal system throughout much of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Norman settlements were characterised by the establishment of baronies, manors, towns and the seeds of the modern county system.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A version of Magna Carta (the Great Charter of Ireland), substituting *Dublin* for *London* and the *Irish Church* for, the English church at the time, the *Catholic Church*, was published in 1216 and the Parliament of Ireland was founded in 1297.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] From the mid-14th century, after the Black Death, Norman settlements in Ireland went into a period of decline.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Norman rulers and the Gaelic Irish elites intermarried and the areas under Norman rule became Gaelicised.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In some parts, a hybrid Hiberno-Norman culture emerged.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In response, the Irish parliament passed the Statutes of Kilkenny in 1367.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] These were a set of laws designed to prevent the assimilation of the Normans into Irish society by requiring English subjects in Ireland to speak English, follow English customs and abide by English law.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] By the end of the 15th century, central English authority in Ireland had all but disappeared, and a renewed Irish culture and language, albeit with Norman influences, was again dominant.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] English Crown control remained relatively unshaken in an amorphous foothold around Dublin known as The Pale, and under the provisions of Poynings' Law of 1494, Irish Parliamentary legislation was subject to the approval of the English Privy Council.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The title of King of Ireland was re-created in 1542 by Henry VIII, King of England, of the Tudor dynasty.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] English rule was reinforced and expanded in Ireland during the latter part of the 16th century, leading to the Tudor conquest of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A near-complete conquest was achieved by the turn of the 17th century, following the Nine Years' War and the Flight of the Earls.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This control was consolidated during the wars and conflicts of the 17th century, including the English and Scottish colonisation in the Plantations of Ireland, the Wars of the Three Kingdoms and the Williamite War.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] During the Irish Confederate Wars (1641–1653), Ireland experienced a catastrophic demographic collapse.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A further 50,000 were sent into indentured servitude in the West Indies.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Petty estimated that 504,000 Catholic Irish and 112,000 Protestant settlers died, and 100,000 people were transported, as a result of the war.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] If a prewar population of 1.5 million is assumed, this would mean that the population was reduced by almost half.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The religious struggles of the 17th century left a deep sectarian division in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Religious allegiance now determined the perception in law of loyalty to the Irish King and Parliament.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] After the passing of the Test Act 1672, and the victory of the forces of the dual monarchy of William and Mary over the Jacobites, Roman Catholics and nonconforming Protestant Dissenters were barred from sitting as members in the Irish Parliament.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Under the emerging Penal Laws, Irish Roman Catholics and Dissenters were increasingly deprived of various civil rights, even the ownership of hereditary property.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Additional regressive punitive legislation followed in 1703, 1709 and 1728.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This completed a comprehensive systemic effort to materially disadvantage Roman Catholics and Protestant Dissenters while enriching a new ruling class of Anglican conformists.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The new Anglo-Irish ruling class became known as the Protestant Ascendancy.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The "Great Frost" struck Ireland and the rest of Europe between December 1739 and September 1741, after a decade of relatively mild winters.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The winters destroyed stored crops of potatoes and other staples, and the poor summers severely damaged harvests.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] An estimated 250,000 people (about one in eight of the population) died from the ensuing pestilence and disease.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Irish government halted export of corn and kept the army in quarters but did little more.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Local gentry and charitable organisations provided relief but could do little to prevent the ensuing mortality.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In the aftermath of the famine, an increase in industrial production and a surge in trade brought a succession of construction booms.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The population soared in the latter part of this century and the architectural legacy of Georgian Ireland was built.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1782, Poynings' Law was repealed, giving Ireland legislative independence from Great Britain for the first time since 1495.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The British government, however, still retained the right to nominate the government of Ireland without the consent of the Irish parliament.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1798, members of the Protestant Dissenter tradition (mainly Presbyterian) made common cause with Roman Catholics in a republican rebellion inspired and led by the Society of United Irishmen, with the aim of creating an independent Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Despite assistance from France the rebellion was put down by British and Irish government and yeomanry forces.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The rebellion lasted from the 24th of May to the 12th of October that year and saw the establishment of the short lived Irish Republic (1798) in the province of Connacht.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] It saw numerous battles across the island with an estimated 30,000 people dead.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] As a direct result of the 1798 rebellion in its aftermath in 1800, the British and Irish parliaments both passed Acts of Union that, with effect from 1 January 1801, merged the Kingdom of Ireland and the Kingdom of Great Britain to create a United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The passage of the Act in the Irish Parliament was ultimately achieved with substantial majorities, having failed on the first attempt in 1799.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] According to contemporary documents and historical analysis, this was achieved through a considerable degree of bribery, with funding provided by the British Secret Service Office, and the awarding of peerages, places and honours to secure votes.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Thus, the parliament in Ireland was abolished and replaced by a united parliament at Westminster in London, though resistance remained, as evidenced by Robert Emmet's failed Irish Rebellion of 1803.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Great Famine of 1845–1851 devastated Ireland, as in those years Ireland's population fell by one-third.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] More than one million people died from starvation and disease, with an additional million people emigrating during the famine, mostly to the United States and Canada.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In the century that followed, an economic depression caused by the famine resulted in a further million people emigrating.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] By the end of the decade, half of all immigration to the United States was from Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The period of civil unrest that followed until the end of the 19th century is referred to as the Land War.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Mass emigration became deeply entrenched and the population continued to decline until the mid-20th century.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Immediately prior to the famine the population was recorded as 8.2 million by the 1841 census.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The population has never returned to this level since.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The population continued to fall until 1961; County Leitrim was the final Irish county to record a population increase post-famine, in 2006.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The 19th and early 20th centuries saw the rise of modern Irish nationalism, primarily among the Roman Catholic population.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The pre-eminent Irish political figure after the Union was Daniel O'Connell.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] He was elected as Member of Parliament for Ennis in a surprise result and despite being unable to take his seat as a Roman Catholic.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] O'Connell spearheaded a vigorous campaign that was taken up by the Prime Minister, the Irish-born soldier and statesman, the Duke of Wellington.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Steering the Catholic Relief Bill through Parliament, aided by future prime minister Robert Peel, Wellington prevailed upon a reluctant George IV to sign the Bill and proclaim it into law.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] George's father had opposed the plan of the earlier Prime Minister, Pitt the Younger, to introduce such a bill following the Union of 1801, fearing Catholic emancipation to be in conflict with the Act of Settlement 1701.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Daniel O'Connell led a subsequent campaign, for the repeal of the Act of Union, which failed.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Later in the century, Charles Stewart Parnell and others campaigned for autonomy within the Union, or "Home Rule".
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Unionists, especially those located in Ulster, were strongly opposed to Home Rule, which they thought would be dominated by Catholic interests.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] After several attempts to pass a Home Rule bill through parliament, it looked certain that one would finally pass in 1914.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] To prevent this from happening, the Ulster Volunteers were formed in 1913 under the leadership of Edward Carson.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Their formation was followed in 1914 by the establishment of the Irish Volunteers, whose aim was to ensure that the Home Rule Bill was passed.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Act was passed but with the "temporary" exclusion of the six counties of Ulster, which later became Northern Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Before it could be implemented, however, the Act was suspended for the duration of the First World War.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Irish Volunteers split into two groups.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The majority, approximately 175,000 in number, under John Redmond, took the name National Volunteers and supported Irish involvement in the war.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A minority, approximately 13,000, retained the Irish Volunteers' name and opposed Ireland's involvement in the war.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Easter Rising of 1916 was carried out by the latter group together with a smaller socialist militia, the Irish Citizen Army.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The British response, executing 15 leaders of the Rising over a period of ten days and imprisoning or interning more than a thousand people, turned the mood of the country in favour of the rebels.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Support for Irish republicanism increased further due to the ongoing war in Europe, as well as the Conscription Crisis of 1918.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The pro-independence republican party, Sinn Féin, received overwhelming endorsement in the 1918 general election, and in 1919 proclaimed an Irish Republic, setting up its own parliament (*Dáil Éireann*) and government.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Simultaneously the Volunteers, which became known as the Irish Republican Army (IRA), launched a three-year guerrilla war, which ended in a truce in July 1921 (although violence continued until June 1922, mostly in Northern Ireland).
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In December 1921, the Anglo-Irish Treaty was concluded between the British government and representatives of the 2nd Dáil.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] It gave Ireland complete independence in its home affairs and practical independence for foreign policy, but an opt-out clause allowed Northern Ireland to remain within the United Kingdom, which it immediately exercised.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Additionally, Members of the Free State Parliament were required to swear an oath of allegiance to the Constitution of the Irish Free State and make a statement of faithfulness to the king.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Disagreements over these provisions led to a split in the nationalist movement and a subsequent Irish Civil War between the new government of the Irish Free State and those opposed to the treaty, led by Éamon de Valera.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The civil war officially ended in May 1923 when de Valera issued a cease-fire order.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] During its first decade, the newly formed Irish Free State was governed by the victors of the civil war.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] When de Valera achieved power, he took advantage of the Statute of Westminster and political circumstances to build upon inroads to greater sovereignty made by the previous government.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The oath was abolished and in 1937 a new constitution was adopted.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This completed a process of gradual separation from the British Empire that governments had pursued since independence.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] However, it was not until 1949 that the state was declared, officially, to be the Republic of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The state was neutral during World War II, but offered clandestine assistance to the Allies, particularly in the potential defence of Northern Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Despite their country's neutrality, approximately 50,000 volunteers from independent Ireland joined the British forces during the war, four being awarded Victoria Crosses.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The German intelligence was also active in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Its operations ended in September 1941 when police made arrests based on surveillance carried out on the key diplomatic legations in Dublin.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] To the authorities, counterintelligence was a fundamental line of defence.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] With a regular army of only slightly over seven thousand men at the start of the war, and with limited supplies of modern weapons, the state would have had great difficulty in defending itself from invasion from either side in the conflict.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Large-scale emigration marked most of the post-WWII period (particularly during the 1950s and 1980s), but beginning in 1987 the economy improved, and the 1990s saw the beginning of substantial economic growth.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This period of growth became known as the Celtic Tiger.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Republic's real GDP grew by an average of 9.6% per annum between 1995 and 1999, in which year the Republic joined the euro.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 2000, it was the sixth-richest country in the world in terms of GDP per capita.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Foster argues the cause was a combination of a new sense of initiative and the entry of American corporations.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] He concludes the chief factors were low taxation, pro-business regulatory policies, and a young, tech-savvy workforce.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] For many multinationals, the decision to do business in Ireland was made easier still by generous incentives from the Industrial Development Authority.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In addition European Union membership was helpful, giving the country lucrative access to markets that it had previously reached only through the United Kingdom, and pumping huge subsidies and investment capital into the Irish economy.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Modernisation brought secularisation in its wake.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The traditionally high levels of religiosity have sharply declined.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Foster points to three factors: First, Irish feminism, largely imported from America with liberal stances on contraception, abortion and divorce, undermined the authority of bishops and priests.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Second, the mishandling of the paedophile scandals humiliated the Church, whose bishops seemed less concerned with the victims and more concerned with covering up for errant priests.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Third, prosperity brought hedonism and materialism that undercut the ideals of saintly poverty.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The post-2008 Irish economic downturn dramatically ended this period of boom.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] GDP fell by 3% in 2008 and by 7.1% in 2009, the worst year since records began (although earnings by foreign-owned businesses continued to grow).
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The state has since experienced deep recession, with unemployment, which doubled during 2009, remaining above 14% in 2012.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Northern Ireland resulted from the division of the United Kingdom by the Government of Ireland Act 1920, and until 1972 was a self-governing jurisdiction within the United Kingdom with its own parliament and prime minister.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Northern Ireland, as part of the United Kingdom, was not neutral during the Second World War, and Belfast suffered four bombing raids in 1941.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Conscription was not extended to Northern Ireland, and roughly an equal number volunteered from Northern Ireland as volunteered from the Republic of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Although Northern Ireland was largely spared the strife of the civil war, in the decades that followed partition there were sporadic episodes of inter-communal violence.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Nationalists, mainly Roman Catholic, wanted to unite Ireland as an independent republic, whereas unionists, mainly Protestant, wanted Northern Ireland to remain in the United Kingdom.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Protestant and Catholic communities in Northern Ireland voted largely along sectarian lines, meaning that the government of Northern Ireland (elected by "first-past-the-post" from 1929) was controlled by the Ulster Unionist Party.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Over time, the minority Catholic community felt increasingly alienated with further disaffection fuelled by practices such as gerrymandering and discrimination in housing and employment.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In the late 1960s, nationalist grievances were aired publicly in mass civil rights protests, which were often confronted by loyalist counter-protests.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The government's reaction to confrontations was seen to be one-sided and heavy-handed in favour of unionists.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Law and order broke down as unrest and inter-communal violence increased.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Northern Ireland government requested the British Army to aid the police and protect the Irish Nationalist population.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1969, the paramilitary Provisional IRA, which favoured the creation of a united Ireland, emerged from a split in the Irish Republican Army and began a campaign against what it called the "British occupation of the six counties".
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Other groups, both the unionist and nationalist participated in violence, and a period known as "the Troubles" began.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] More than 3,600 deaths resulted over the subsequent three decades of conflict.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Owing to the civil unrest during the Troubles, the British government suspended home rule in 1972 and imposed direct rule.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] There were several unsuccessful attempts to end the Troubles politically, such as the Sunningdale Agreement of 1973.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1998, following a ceasefire by the Provisional IRA and multi-party talks, the Good Friday Agreement was concluded as a treaty between the British and Irish governments, annexing the text agreed in the multi-party talks.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The substance of the Agreement (formally referred to as the Belfast Agreement) was later endorsed by referendums in both parts of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Agreement restored self-government to Northern Ireland on the basis of power-sharing in a regional Executive drawn from the major parties in a new Northern Ireland Assembly, with entrenched protections for the two main communities.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Executive is jointly headed by a First Minister and deputy First Minister drawn from the unionist and nationalist parties.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Violence had decreased greatly after the Provisional IRA and loyalist ceasefires in 1994, and in 2005, the Provisional IRA announced the end of its armed campaign and an independent commission supervised its disarmament and that of other nationalist and unionist paramilitary organisations.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Assembly and power-sharing Executive were suspended several times but were restored again in 2007.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In that year the British government officially ended its military support of the police in Northern Ireland (Operation Banner) and began withdrawing troops.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] On 27 June 2012, Northern Ireland's deputy first minister and former IRA commander, Martin McGuinness, shook hands with Queen Elizabeth II in Belfast, symbolising reconciliation between the two sides.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The island is divided between the Republic of Ireland, an independent state, and Northern Ireland, a constituent country of the United Kingdom.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] They share an open border and both are part of the Common Travel Area and as a consequence, there is free movement of people, goods, services and capital across the border.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Republic of Ireland is a parliamentary democracy based on the Westminster system, with a written constitution and a popularly elected president whose role is mostly ceremonial.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Oireachtas is a bicameral parliament, composed of Dáil Éireann (the Dáil), a house of representatives, and Seanad Éireann (the Seanad), an upper house.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The government is headed by a prime minister, the Taoiseach, who is appointed by the president on the nomination of the Dáil.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Republic of Ireland today ranks among the wealthiest countries in the world in terms of GDP per capita and in 2015 was ranked the sixth most developed nation in the world by the United Nations' Human Development Index.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A period of rapid economic expansion from 1995 onwards became known as the Celtic Tiger period, was brought to an end by the post-2008 Irish economic downturn and an economic depression in 2009.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] According to the 2024 Global Peace Index, Ireland is the second most peaceful country in the world.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Northern Ireland is a part of the United Kingdom with a local executive and assembly which exercise devolved powers.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The executive is jointly headed by the first and deputy first minister, with the ministries being allocated in proportion to each party's representation in the assembly.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ultimately political power is held by the UK government, from which Northern Ireland has gone through intermittent periods of direct rule during which devolved powers have been suspended.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Northern Ireland elects 18 of the UK House of Commons' 650 MPs.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The Northern Ireland Secretary is a cabinet-level post in the British government.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Along with England and Wales and with Scotland, Northern Ireland forms one of the three separate legal jurisdictions of the UK, all of which share the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom as their court of final appeal.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] As part of the Good Friday Agreement, the British and Irish governments agreed on the creation of all-island institutions and areas of cooperation.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The North/South Ministerial Council is an institution through which ministers from the Government of Ireland and the Northern Ireland Executive agree all-island policies.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] At least six of these policy areas must have an associated all-island "implementation body", and at least six others must be implemented separately in each jurisdiction.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The implementation bodies are: Waterways Ireland, the Food Safety Promotion Board, InterTradeIreland, the Special European Union Programmes Body, the North/South Language Body and the Foyle, Carlingford and Irish Lights Commission.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The British–Irish Intergovernmental Conference provides for co-operation between the Government of Ireland and the Government of the United Kingdom on all matters of mutual interest, especially Northern Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The North/South Inter-Parliamentary Association is a joint parliamentary forum for the island of Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] It has no formal powers but operates as a forum for discussing matters of common concern between the respective legislatures.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ireland is located in the north-west of Europe, between latitudes 51° and 56° N, and longitudes 11° and 5° W.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] It is separated from Great Britain by the Irish Sea and the North Channel, which has a width of 23 kilometres (14 mi) at its narrowest point.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] To the west is the northern Atlantic Ocean and to the south is the Celtic Sea, which lies between Ireland and Brittany, in France.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ireland has a total area of 84,421 km2 (32,595 mi2), of which the Republic of Ireland occupies 83 percent.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ireland and Great Britain, together with many nearby smaller islands, are known collectively as the British Isles.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] As the term *British Isles* can be controversial in relation to Ireland, the alternate term *Britain and Ireland* is sometimes used as a neutral term for the islands.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] A ring of coastal mountains surrounds low plains at the centre of the island.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The highest of these is Carrauntoohil (Irish: *Corrán Tuathail*) in County Kerry, which rises to 1,039 m (3,409 ft) above sea level.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The most arable land lies in the province of Leinster.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Western areas are mainly mountainous and rocky with green panoramic vistas.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] River Shannon, the island's longest river at 360.5 km (224 mi) long, rises in County Cavan in the north-west and flows through Limerick in the midwest.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The island consists of varied geological provinces.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In the west, around County Galway and County Donegal, is a medium- to high-grade metamorphic and igneous complex of Caledonide affinity, similar to the Scottish Highlands.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Across southeast Ulster and extending southwest to Longford and south to Navan is a province of Ordovician and Silurian rocks, with similarities to the Southern Uplands province of Scotland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Further south, along the County Wexford coastline, is an area of granite intrusives into more Ordovician and Silurian rocks, like that found in Wales.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In the southwest, around Bantry Bay and the mountains of MacGillycuddy's Reeks, is an area of substantially deformed, lightly metamorphosed Devonian-aged rocks.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This partial ring of "hard rock" geology is covered by a blanket of Carboniferous limestone over the centre of the country, giving rise to a comparatively fertile and lush landscape.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The west-coast district of the Burren around Lisdoonvarna has well-developed karst features.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Significant stratiform lead-zinc mineralisation is found in the limestones around Silvermines and Tynagh.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Hydrocarbon exploration is ongoing following the first major find at the Kinsale Head gas field off Cork in the mid-1970s.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 1999, economically significant finds of natural gas were made in the Corrib Gas Field off the County Mayo coast.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This has increased activity off the west coast in parallel with the "West of Shetland" step-out development from the North Sea hydrocarbon province.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In 2000, the Helvick oil field was discovered, which was estimated to contain over 28 million barrels (4,500,000 m3) of oil.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The island's lush vegetation, a product of its mild climate and frequent rainfall, earns it the sobriquet *the Emerald Isle*.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Overall, Ireland has a mild but changeable oceanic climate with few extremes.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The climate is typically insular and temperate, avoiding the extremes in temperature of many other areas in the world at similar latitudes.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] This is a result of the moist winds which ordinarily prevail from the southwestern Atlantic.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Precipitation falls throughout the year but is light overall, particularly in the east.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The west tends to be wetter on average and prone to Atlantic storms, especially in the late autumn and winter months.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] These occasionally bring destructive winds and higher total rainfall to these areas, as well as sometimes snow and hail.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] The regions of north County Galway and east County Mayo have the highest incidents of recorded lightning annually for the island, with lightning occurring approximately five to ten days per year in these areas.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Munster, in the south, records the least snow whereas Ulster, in the north, records the most.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Inland areas are warmer in summer and colder in winter.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Usually around 40 days of the year are below freezing 0 °C (32 °F) at inland weather stations, compared to 10 days at coastal stations.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Ireland is sometimes affected by heat waves, most recently in 1995, 2003, 2006, 2013 and 2018.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] In common with the rest of Europe, Ireland experienced unusually cold weather during the winter of 2010–11.
[src:ireland/ireland-p01] Temperatures fell as low as −17.2 °C (1 °F) in County Mayo on 20 December and up to a metre (3 ft) of snow fell in mountainous areas.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Unlike Great Britain which had a land bridge with mainland Europe, Ireland only had an ice bridge ending around 14,000 years ago at the end of the last ice age and as a result, it has fewer land animal and plant species than Great Britain or mainland Europe.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] There are 55 mammal species in Ireland, and of them, only 26 land mammal species are considered native to Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Some species, such as, the red fox, hedgehog and badger, are very common, whereas others, like the Irish hare, red deer and pine marten are less so.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Aquatic wildlife, such as species of sea turtle, shark, seal, whale, and dolphin, are common off the coast.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] About 400 species of birds have been recorded in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Many of these are migratory, including the barn swallow.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Several different habitat types are found in Ireland, including farmland, open woodland, temperate broadleaf and mixed forests, conifer plantations, peat bogs and a variety of coastal habitats.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] However, agriculture drives current land use patterns in Ireland, limiting natural habitat preserves, particularly for larger wild mammals with greater territorial needs.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] With no large apex predators in Ireland other than humans and dogs, such populations of animals as semi-wild deer that cannot be controlled by smaller predators, such as the fox, are controlled by annual culling.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] There are no snakes in Ireland, and only one species of reptile (the common lizard) is native to the island.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Extinct species include the Irish elk, the great auk, brown bear and the wolf.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Some previously extinct birds, such as the golden eagle, have been reintroduced after decades of extirpation.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Ireland is now one of the least forested countries in Europe.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Until the end of the Middle Ages, Ireland was heavily forested.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Native species include deciduous trees such as oak, ash, hazel, birch, alder, willow, aspen, rowan and hawthorn, as well as evergreen trees such Scots pine, yew, holly and strawberry trees.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Only about 10% of Ireland today is woodland; most of this is non-native conifer plantations, and only 2% is native woodland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] The average woodland cover of European countries is over 33%.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] In the Republic, about 389,356 hectares (3,893.56 km2) is owned by the state, mainly by the forestry service Coillte.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Remnants of native forest can be found scattered around the island, in particular in the Killarney National Park.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Much of the land is now covered with pasture and there are many species of wild-flower.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Gorse (*Ulex europaeus*), a wild furze, is commonly found growing in the uplands and ferns are plentiful in the more moist regions, especially in the western parts.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] It is home to hundreds of plant species, some of them unique to the island, and has been "invaded" by some grasses, such as *Spartina anglica*.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] The algal and seaweed flora is that of the cold-temperate variety.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] The total number of species is 574 The island has been invaded by some algae, some of which are now well established.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Because of its mild climate, many species, including sub-tropical species such as palm trees, are grown in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Phytogeographically, Ireland belongs to the Atlantic European province of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] The island can be subdivided into two ecoregions: the Celtic broadleaf forests and North Atlantic moist mixed forests.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] The long history of agricultural production, coupled with modern intensive agricultural methods such as pesticide and fertiliser use and runoff from contaminants into streams, rivers and lakes, has placed pressure on biodiversity in Ireland.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] A land of green fields for crop cultivation and cattle rearing limits the space available for the establishment of native wild species.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Hedgerows, however, traditionally used for maintaining and demarcating land boundaries, act as a refuge for native wild flora.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] This ecosystem stretches across the countryside and acts as a network of connections to preserve remnants of the ecosystem that once covered the island.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Subsidies under the Common Agricultural Policy, which supported agricultural practices that preserved hedgerow environments, are undergoing reforms.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] 32% of Ireland's greenhouse gas emissions are correlated to agriculture.
[src:ireland/ireland-p02] Forested areas typically consist of monoculture plantations of non-native species, which may result in habitats that are not suitable for supporting native species of invertebrates.
